<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Embassy Construction Program Planned  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concerned about the security of U.S.
diplomats, the Clinton administration hopes to lay the groundwork
for construction of between 60 and 100 embassies over the next
decade, a top State Department official says.
</P>
<P>
   But there also is concern whether Congress will be willing to
pay for the work.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has given high priority to the issue since
the Aug. 7, 1998 bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania in which 224 people, including 12 Americans, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Osama bin Laden, a Saudi exile believed to be living in
Afghanistan, is wanted for the bombings, and there is concern he
may strike again.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said bin Laden's agents have been keeping U.S. embassies
under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said last week that the
United States will continue to do what it can ''to try to hunt down
the terrorists. Their day will come, and there is no statute of
limitations, and we will pursue them as necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   To bolster embassy security, the State Department official said,
the administration hopes to set in motion a process that will lead
to the construction of between six and 10 embassies a year over the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   A commission headed by retired Adm. William Crowe, a former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, has recommended that the
government spend $1.4 billion over 10 years to enhance the safety
of American diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   The administration estimates that 85 percent of overseas
facilities do not meet minimum security requirements. Since the
1998 bombings, security upgrades have taken place at some overseas
posts. Still, officials say there is no substitute for having a
100-foot buffer zones separating these facilities from the nearest
public areas.
</P>
<P>
   Often, that means acquiring property and building new
installations, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers are taken aback by the staggering costs projected
for the security work.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't keep spending $100 million on embassies,'' said Sen.
Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the State Department is concerned about the potential
for a new round of terrorist activity, possibly linked to Monday's
anniversary of the East Africa bombings.
</P>
<P>
   A travel advisory issued in June advised American travelers to
keep the Aug. 7 anniversary in mind and to take appropriate
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Embassies around the world have been in a high state of alert
since the bombing and State Department officials were unaware of a
previous alert that lasted as long.
</P>
<P>
   As for bin Laden, the administration has had no success in
bringing him to justice.
</P>
<P>
   At U.S. prodding, the U.N. Security Council last year imposed
sanctions against Afghanistan for its refusal to hand bin Laden
over.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings last week, the United States and Russia agreed to
work together to further tighten the Security Council sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
