<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blige Offers Aid To Victim's Family  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Mo. (AP) -- Grammy-winning singer Mary J. Blige is
offering support to the families of two black men fatally shot by
two white police officers during a drug raid.
</P>
<P>
   Blige briefly attended a rally Friday night at the restaurant
where Earl Murray and Ronald Beasley were shot June 12. Blige is a
supporter of the National Action Network, a civil rights
organization formed by the Rev. Al Sharpton of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 36, and Beasley, 36, were unarmed when they were shot in
Murray's car by undercover police. Police had planned to arrest
Murray on drug charges and said Beasley was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said the shootings were justified because Murray
tried to ram the officers with his car during the arrest. Relatives
and civil rights activists have suggested police used excessive
force because the men were shot numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings are under investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
