<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: 'Hurt' by Attacks on Wife  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton says opponents of his
wife's run for the Senate from New York are trying to muddy the
campaign playing field through personal attacks intended to confuse
voters and unfairly incite resentment against her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the bottom line as far as he is concerned is that
Hillary Rodham Clinton is ''a good person'' and well qualified for
the Senate. ''The reason people ought to vote for her is, it's good
for them and for their kids and for their future.''
</P>
<P>
   The president commented Sunday as he concluded a whirlwind
weekend of fund-raising events that collected an estimated $525,000
for his wife's campaign. He planned to return to Washington
sometime Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the things that hurts me the most (is) if you listen to
the tenor of the campaign against her it's basically, 'Don't vote
for her because she's not from here; don't vote for her because why
is she doing this,'' Clinton said. ''Let me see if I can get you to
resent her.'''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to supporters on Martha's Vineyard who paid $1,000
apiece to hear from both Clintons, neither the president nor the
first lady mentioned the name of her opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio,
R-N.Y. Nor did Clinton cite examples of allegedly unfair
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The president has said previously that he worries more about the
outcome of his wife's campaign than he ever did about any of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   And he made clear he still believes he has cause to worry.
</P>
<P>
   ''If voters in New York can get really confused, that's the only
way she can lose,'' Clinton said. ''Because if they vote for the
strongest person, or the most qualified person, or the person who
could do the most, or the person with whom they agree, she wins.
</P>
<P>
   ''They know that,'' he said of his wife's GOP opposition.
''That's why you have seen the campaign unfold the way it has.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for a counter campaign of personal testimonials.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing she most needs is for people like you to tell other
people they know, 'I know this woman. She is a good person, she is
a great public servant and she ought to be the next senator.'''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the presidential election, Clinton also said Vice
President Al Gore's campaign and the New York Senate race together
could determine the fate of legal abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ''This election is also a choice about choice,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The next president will likely make between two and four
nominations for the Supreme Court, ''and I hope Al Gore will be
making them,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But those nominations must be confirmed by the Senate, Clinton
added.
</P>
<P>
   ''So it matters. Every last Senate seat is of critical
importance in this presidential race.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore, whom Clinton is vigorously supporting to succeed him,
and Mrs. Clinton support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't believe that we should keep Roe v. Wade,'' Clinton
said, referring to Republicans generally and the Supreme Court
decision legalizing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons were the guests of honor Sunday at two parties
expected to bring in $400,000. The fanciest affair was an intimate
dinner for 65 with entertainment by singer Carly Simon and a ticket
price of $15,000 per couple.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton played the saxaphone and, according to guests, teamed
with Simon on a version of ''My Funny Valentine.'' The crowd sang
''Happy Birthday to the president who will turn 54 on Aug. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Friday, the president offered himself as the star
attraction at fund-raising parties on Martha's Vineyard, the
neighboring resort island of Nantucket and the Kennedy family
compound on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his family have vacationed on Martha's Vineyard
nearly every year of his presidency. This year's was the shortest
stay -- just three days.
</P>
<P>
   The first family decided not to take a full-fledged summer
vacation this year to focus on campaigning for her Senate race and
fund-raising for Gore and other Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
