<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Drops 18; Nasdaq Adds 9  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened mixed Monday, as investors
prepared for another day of choppy trading on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 17.67 at 10,750.08.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 0.02 at 1,462.91, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 9.25 at 3,796.61.
</P>
<P>
   Investors continue to search for clues as to whether the Federal
Reserve Board will raise interest rates at its next meeting Aug.
22. But much of the economic data released recently has been of
little help, offering conflicting figures that can be interpreted
several ways.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on Friday the Labor Department reported that the
nation's unemployment rate was unchanged at 4 percent in July,
close to a three-decade low, despite the loss of 108,000 payroll
jobs during the month, the biggest setback in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the losses resulted from 290,000 temporary government
workers laid off in July because their work on the census was
finished.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed private payrolls actually rose by 138,000
during the month. However, analysts noted that last month's gain in
private sector jobs was down significantly from a jump of 242,000
in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times since last summer in
an effort to stave off inflation, and investors hope the latest
figures are a sign that strategy is working.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered decliners on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 107.35 million shares, down
from Friday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.58 at 505.21.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.14 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.18 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.12 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.66 percent.
</P>
