<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rabbis Delay Debate on Temple Mount  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's top rabbis put off discussion on
Monday of a proposal to build a synagogue at one of the most
sensitive spots in the Middle East -- the Temple Mount in the Old
City of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The hill where the holy Jewish temples once stood is now the
site of the Dome of the Rock shrine and Al Aqsa Mosque, the
third-holiest site in Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The mufti of Jerusalem, Ikrema Sabri, who is the senior Islamic
official in the holy city, warned that building a synagogue on the
hill would set off major chaos in the region and start a war ''that
only God knows where it would lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chief Rabbinical Council, the top policy-making body for
Israel's Orthodox Jewish establishment, appointed a committee to
study all the aspects of the issue while protecting the historic
and religious rights of Jews on the Temple Mount, said council
spokesman Shaika Rosenfeld. He said the council repeated its
earlier ruling that Jews are not allowed to enter the Temple Mount
because of its holiness and concerns about ritual purity.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of control over Jerusalem and its holy sites scuttled
a summit meeting outside Washington last month between Israeli and
Palestinian leaders, who were trying to agree on a framework for a
peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the council decision, there was Jewish-Muslim
violence on the Temple Mount. Angry Palestinians surrounded a group
of Israelis they thought were praying there. Israeli police said a
Muslim guard hit one of the Israelis with a two-way radio. The
guard later turned himself in to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld said Chief Rabbi Eliahu Bakshi-Doron, president of the
council, decided to postpone the debate after a public outcry over
the issue. No new date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The chief rabbi of Haifa, Shaar-Yeshuv Hacohen, had prepared the
proposal to build the synagogue. He disagreed with the opinion of
most Rabbinical authorities that Jews may not enter the Temple
Mount.
</P>
<P>
   Sabri, the mufti, called on the council to reject the proposal,
not just delay the debate. He said the hill is Islamic and ''is not
subject to negotiations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 1152 </TRAILER>
