<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Changes Cabinet  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Reacting to criticism over the pace of
economic reform, President Kim Dae-jung replaced almost half of his
Cabinet on Monday, including the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   Taking over as finance minister is Jin Nyum, South Korea's chief
budget planner for two years. Jin's career has spanned nearly four
decades under five administrations starting in 1963. He was trade
minister and labor minister in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should strengthen competitiveness and straighten market
order by successfully completing restructuring'' of the financial
sector, Jin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Kim retained Prime Minister Lee Han-dong in his largely
ceremonial post. But he made changes in eight of the 19 Cabinet
posts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the replaced ministers held economic jobs and were
responsible for implementing reforms drawn up at the start of the
Asian financial crisis of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have achieved a lot, but we shouldn't be carried away with
the achievement. There is much to do,'' presidential aides quoted
Kim as telling the new ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization was not expected to affect the government's
engagement policy toward North Korea, because all Cabinet members
handling inter-Korea affairs were retained.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ''sunshine'' policy toward the communist North
calls for economic exchanges and cooperation. Presidential aides
said the new economic team will strongly support that policy.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's economy has recovered in the past three years, but
analysts and opposition lawmakers accused the government of
mishandling the nation's top conglomerate and other failures,
leading to stagnancy in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Paeng Sung-il, a research fellow at Daewoo Economic Research
Institute, said Jin's economic team will help restore market
confidence in government policies.
</P>
<P>
   Jin replaced Lee Hun-jai, who was named to head the finance
ministry in January. Lee was the government's chief financial
regulator before taking the post.
</P>
<P>
   Lee led a high-profile restructuring of South Korea's financial
sector under a program worked out in exchange for a $58 billion
loan from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Under Lee's direction, dozens of financially weak banks were
closed, restoring foreign investor confidence in South Korea's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But he was criticized for his handling of Hyundai, South Korea's
largest conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   A major Hyundai subsidiary, Hyundai Construction and Engineering
Co., recently avoided default on payments only with
government-arranged loans.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai's problems were blamed partly on the government's
failure to enforce regulations to restructure South Korea's
inefficient, family-controlled conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai, which has more than 50 subsidiaries, has failed to keep
its repeated promises to slim down by selling or spinning off
unprofitable subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the Cabinet posts in the shakeup were economic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 1241 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000807.0023 </DOCNO>
