<HEADLINE> Israeli Leader's Brother in Trouble  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE COPANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Police on Monday recommended bribery charges be
brought against the brother of Israel's newly elected president,
saying he persuaded a rival in a mayoral race to quit with the
promise of a top job.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors must still decide whether to indict Lior Katsav, the
mayor of Kiryat Malachi and brother of newly elected President
Moshe Katsav.
</P>
<P>
   The police allege Katsav promised a rival that he and an aide
would get high-level positions if they withdrew from the 1998
mayoral race. The rival agreed and after Katsav was elected mayor
of the poor southern town, the former candidate and his aide were
given jobs, police spokesman Ofer Sivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Katsav was selected by parliament last week to be Israel's
president, beating former prime minister and Nobel laureate Shimon
Peres.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was held three years early after incumbent Ezer Weizman
was driven out by a financial scandal. Weizman resigned July 10
after admitting he received more than $350,000 from a French
textile magnate. Although no charges were filed, the attorney
general ruled Weizman had acted improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Lior Katsav denied the charges against him, saying the deal was
arranged in an agreement that was overseen and signed by a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Katsav signed the agreement innocently and for the good of the
community,'' spokesman Yossi Peretz said.
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Katsav's spokeswoman told Israel radio it was a ''private
matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
