<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former harness maker to Erie Canal mules closing after nearly 150 years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Not many businesses can boast of surviving
for more than 100 years after the departure of some of their
biggest clients.
</P>
<P>
   At Jansen Bros. there is an abundance of work to this day at the
shop Henrich Jansen built crafting leather harnesses for mules that
pulled boats along the Erie Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed since those days, of course. Jansen Bros.
now does automobile interior work and luggage repair along with
making and repairing leather goods for work animals and show
horses.
</P>
<P>
   But the end is near.
</P>
<P>
   The founder's great-grandson, Henry Jansen, will turn 73 next
month and plans to close his shop shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the end of the line when it comes to this business,''
Jansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Henrich Jansen honed his skills in the city's Canal District in
the 1850s, kept busy by the ever-present need for mule harnesses.
He officially established Jansen Bros. in 1863.
</P>
<P>
   While Henry Jansen followed the footsteps of his
great-grandfather, grandfather and father into the shop in the
city, the next generation has chosen a different path.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh yeah, they all tried it at one time or another,'' Henry
Jansen said of his three children. ''But let's face it. This place
ain't the modern world.''
</P>
<P>
   Stitching horses, antique trunks, anvils and other relics from a
bygone era cram the dusty shop - items eventually destined for a
local children's museum, which plans to showcase Jansen in an
exhibit late next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bonny Ryder, founder of the MUDPIES museum, said Jansen's
voluminous business records offer an intriguing glimpse into
Buffalo's mercantile past.
</P>
<P>
   ''Henry is a dying breed,'' Ryder said. ''He's a craftsman who
can do the most amazing things with leather. You don't see that too
much anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jansen, who sold the company's retail business two years ago but
has continued to do leather repairs, plans on doing occasional
leather work in the garage of his Eden home. But he said his main
focus will be traveling with his wife in their motor home and
spending time with their grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he said he has more work than he can handle.
Recent orders include making leather handles for an antique trunk
and an elaborate harness for a a carrousel horse, and installing
several tiny metal insignias, each bearing the name of a horse, on
a leather belt.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of his business still involves horse-related items
such as saddles, bridles and blankets. He also does luggage repair
and a lot of automobile upholstery; restoring antique cars is one
of his passions.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jansen, ''I tell people we'll make anything. But the
impossible takes a little longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
