<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City says landlord's $6.65 million lawsuit is frivilous  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) - A city attorney said he would ask a court to
force a landlord to pay up to $10,000 for filing a frivolous
lawsuit against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Property owner Paul Meyer claims in a $6.65 million lawsuit
against the city that he lost ''significant'' business after the
city posted slum property signs in front of two of his rental
properties in 1999. Meyer contended the properties were in
compliance with city codes when the signs were posted and accused
the city of libel.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear that this is a lawsuit that is frivolous and
intended to harass and we are asking the court to impose
sanctions,'' Assistant Corporation Counsel David Tehan said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Tehan said the $10,000 would cover the cost of defending the
case and attorneys' fees.
</P>
<P>
   The city posted the signs in February 1999. The signs listed
Meyer's name, address, phone number and said his properties were in
violation of city housing code and contributed to the blight of the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In legal papers responding to Meyer's allegations, Tehan
countered that the information was true and written without malice
so the signs were not libelous.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer sought a court order last year to have the signs removed.
However, a judge ruled the signs were a legal and proper method for
the city to force rental property owners to bring their properties
up to code. Meyer filed a lawsuit in state Supreme Court in
February.
</P>
<P>
   The city codes department posts slum property signs after citing
a landlord for more than three violations within a year, Tehan
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
