<HEADLINE> Israelis Wound 3 at Lebanon Border  </HEADLINE>
By ZEINA KARAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli soldiers shot at stone-throwers
preparing a Molotov cocktail near Fatima Gate on the
Israeli-Lebanese border Monday, injuring a teen-ager and two
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second violent incident in the area in two days; both
times Israeli soldiers opened fire. One man was wounded Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers have deployed in much of southern Lebanon, but
not near Fatima Gate, where hurling stones at an Israeli
observation post has become a ritual for visitors from Lebanon
since Israel withdrew its troops from southern Lebanon May 24.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has not explained why peacekeepers have
stayed away from the gate at Kfar Kila village.
</P>
<P>
   Katya Jarjoura of Montreal, a 25-year-old free-lance reporter
for Radio Canada, was hit in the abdomen by shrapnel from a bullet
and Ali Dia, 50, a Lebanese journalist working for Agence
France-Presse, was injured in both legs, the two told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Tarek Mohammed Hussein, 13, was injured in his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were hurling stones at the Israelis when a soldier emerged
from the outpost and opened fire, hitting me in my toes,'' Hussein
said from his hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   Dia, who had the shrapnel removed from his legs and was
discharged from the hospital in Nabatiyeh before dawn, said youths
were throwing stones at the Israeli outpost when he and Jarjoura
reached the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Two Israeli soldiers emerged from the outpost, and when they
saw that the youths were preparing to throw a Molotov, they fired
shots at the youths,'' Dia said. The youths then threw their
firebomb.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem initially said the army
was not involved in the shooting. Later, a spokesman acknowledged
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a Molotov cocktail tossed, soldiers returned fire,
and as far as we know, only the man who tossed the Molotov cocktail
was injured,'' Maj. Yarden Vatikay said. ''In an incident such as
this one, all those who are near the rioters -- near those who throw
Molotov cocktails -- are at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarjoura and Dia said they gathered shortly after midnight
waiting for possible deployment of Lebanese security forces in
border villages.
</P>
<P>
   Jarjoura, who came to Lebanon two months ago, said doctors
removed three pieces of shrapnel from her abdomen and she hoped to
be released from the hospital on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not discouraged, '' she said. ''I would still like to
give it a chance here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a Lebanese man was wounded in the leg when Israeli
soldiers fired into another crowd of stone-throwers at the Fatima
Gate. The Israeli army said a bullet shot by Israeli soldiers
struck the ground and the man was injured by a ricocheting stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
