<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State board meets to certify two-way Democratic primary  </HEADLINE>
With BC-NY--NY Senate, Bjt
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Board of Elections on Monday
settled on a Sept. 12 Democratic U.S. Senate primary ballot that
would have Hillary Rodham Clinton face off against a New York City
orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The primary would pit the first lady against Dr. Mark McMahon,
who has complained about Clinton's lack of New York roots. She
moved into the state in January.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island is the Republican Party's
U.S. Senate nominee and faces no primary challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been facing a potential six-way primary, but four
other potential competitors were knocked off the primary ballot on
Friday by a state Supreme Court justice in Brooklyn. While that
ruling could be appealed, state board officials said they believed
it would stand.
</P>
<P>
   Removed from the Democratic ballot for failing to meet the
petition requirements were: Irving Gelb, a taxi driver; Jimmy
McMillan, a retired letter carrier; Eric Melendez, a civil engineer
who finished last in a four-way Democratic U.S. Senate primary in
1998; and Peter Ruane, a retired New York City police lieutenant.
On Friday, Melendez endorsed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Senate candidates must collect the signatures of at least 15,000
party members statewide to win a spot on the ballot. McMahon had
collected more than 40,000 while Clinton didn't need to collect any
because she was the official candidate designee from the party's
state convention in May.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of a six-way primary emerged last month when the
two Democratic members of the state Board of Elections refused to
join their two Republican colleagues on the board in voting to
remove the four Democratic contenders from the primary ballot.
Three board votes are needed to declare a petition invalid.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's campaign had hoped for a six-way primary as a
means of diluting the anti-Clinton vote, thus hurting McMahon's
chances in the primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
