<DOCNO> APW20000807.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High court orders new trial for convicted child molester  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The state Supreme Court ruled on Monday
that a Stamford man convicted of sexually assaulting his
girlfriend's daughter was denied a fair trial because of improper
comments by the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The high court found Assistant State's Attorney Nancy Dolinsky
violated Andrew Alexander's constitutional rights to due process
when she expressed her own opinion on the credibility of the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Dolinsky said in closing arguments that the 12-year-old girl was
telling the truth because she was young, and therefore honest, and
that no child would make up a story about being abused.
</P>
<P>
   ''Statements such as these are likely to sway a jury in favor of
the prosecutor's argument without properly considering the facts of
evidence,'' Judge Flemming L. Norcott Jr. wrote in the unanimous
decision. ''This is especially significant in the present case,
where the credibility of the victim and the defendant comprised the
principal issue of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The court found the prosecutor improperly appealed to the
emotions of the jury as she described the naive, vulnerable victim
and the strong and powerful Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander was convicted in 1995 of fourth-degree sexual assault
and risk of injury to a minor. The victim testified that after
Alexander moved in with her mother in Stamford in 1990, he began
coming into her bedroom at night and molesting her. The girl, who
was 8 years old at the time, said the abuse continued for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander was sentenced to one year in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully this will send out a warning to prosecutors who try
child abuse cases that they better be careful in terms of the
analogies they use in arguing their case,'' said Alexander's public
defender, Monte Radler. ''You can well imagine that the sympathies
of juries ordinarily lie with the children. The whole area is
certainly subject to abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stamford prosecutor's office did not return a message
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision upholds a ruling by the Appellate
Court overturning Alexander's conviction. The case now returns to
Stamford Superior Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
