<HEADLINE> Entry Added to Yugoslavia Elections  </HEADLINE>
By JOVANA GEC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Formalizing the breach in opposition
ranks, a coalition opposed to Slobodan Milosevic nominated its own
presidential candidate Monday, the third challenger to Milosevic
for Yugoslavia's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Serbia's opposition parties endorsed the candidacy of
Vojislav Kostunica of the small center-right Serbian Democratic
Party, a moderate nationalist widely respected for his decade-long
uncompromising opposition to the autocratic Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica's nomination came a day after the Serbian Renewal
Movement, the single largest opposition party, broke ranks with the
rest of the democratic opposition and put forward its own
candidate, Belgrade Mayor Vojislav Mihajlovic. The move is likely
to split opposition votes and diminish chances of success.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said yes because of the public,'' Kostunica, 56, said after
the nomination. ''It's my moral duty to the opposition, and not my
wish.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-Milosevic votes will be sliced further by the
ultranationalist Serbian Radical Party's announcement Monday that
it had picked its own candidate as well. The party, known for its
''Serbs First'' policies, put up Tomislav Nikolic.
</P>
<P>
   According to all recent independent polls, Kostunica, who has a
Ph.D. in law, enjoys the most public support of the various
challengers among Serbs, who are disappointed with other bickering
leaders. He has not been linked to the corruption which has
tarnished the reputations of some other opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica said the presence of other candidates in the crowded
field is aimed at preventing him from reaching a likely second
round in the elections, to be held two weeks later if no one wins
an outright majority on Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Radical leader Vojislav Seselj said Nikolic, 48, had the best
chances because of his determination to protect ''Serbian national
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikolic, known locally as ''Toma the gravedigger'' because he
worked as the chief of a local graveyard, said his victory ''will
be the first in a series for the Radicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the opposition Democratic Alternative party
criticized the decision by Vuk Draskovic's Serbian Renewal Movement
to press ahead on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one, no single party has the right to gamble with the
country's national interests and bring down the entire nation,''
the party's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   But another leader, Zoran Djindjic, expressed hope that
''eighteen parties in this coalition are strong enough to field the
best candidate to beat Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Many have been furious with Draskovic for months because of his
alleged involvement in illegal business operations in Belgrade and
for serving in Milosevic's government as a Yugoslav deputy prime
minister until he was fired during the 1999 NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica earlier urged the pro-Western administration in
Montenegro, which along with Serbia forms the Yugoslav federation,
to participate in the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the pro-Western government of Montenegrin President Milo
Djukanovic has refused to take part in the September elections,
saying recent changes in the constitution unfairly improved
Milosevic's chances.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's opposition parties managed to unite against Milosevic
only once -- in 1996-1997 -- for massive protests over attempts to
annul local elections that brought them into power in all of
Serbia's major towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the elections, the democratic alliance fell
apart, leaving it unable to seriously contest the 1997 Serbian
presidential and parliamentary elections, won by Milosevic's
Socialists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
