<HEADLINE> City's cultural affairs chief fined for ethics violation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The city's cultural affairs chief has been fined
$500 by the city's ethics board for hosting a political fund-raiser
at his house last year that included guests with business dealings
with the city, the board announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Schuyler Chapin, appointed by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in 1994 as
the commissioner of the Department of Cultural Affairs, held a
fund-raiser at his house for former mayoral candidate Fran Reiter
in October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Reiter, a former deputy mayor under Giuliani who also headed the
mayor's 1997 re-election campaign and served as the head of the
city's tourism bureau, has since dropped out of the 2001 mayor's
race.
</P>
<P>
   Chapin was on vacation Monday and could not be reached for
comment, but in a statement to the Conflicts of Interest Board, he
acknowledged that he had acted improperly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several of the attendees to this fund-raiser had, at the time
of the fund-raiser, business dealings with the Department of
Cultural Affairs and, or, the city,'' Chapin said. ''I freely and
voluntarily admit that my conduct in co-hosting this fund-raiser
violated the New York City Charter.''
</P>
<P>
   Chapin said before he hosted the fund-raiser that an attorney
informed him that he would not be violating any city rules.
</P>
<P>
   The city charter bars high-level city officials like Chapin from
seeking political contributions for others or from hosting
fund-raisers whose guests include people who have business dealings
with their agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
