<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists trying to create 'Jersey tomatoes' in greenhouse  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - Rutgers University scientists say
they're close to finding a way for New Jersey farmers to grow the
famed ''Jersey tomatoes'' profitably in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have been trying to duplicate the juicy, plump
tomatoes that have become the state's premier crop by growing them
in nutrient-enriched water in greenhouses.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists control the temperature at a one-acre greenhouse
in Columbus, Burlington County, keeping it at 72 degrees during the
day, 68 degrees at night. They adjust the light so that the
tomatoes are kept in darkness for six to eight hours a day,
sprinkle ladybugs on the plants to fight other insects, and
regulate the humidity to cultivate the tomatoes' sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   ''It took us a long time to manipulate the growing conditions so
we could come up with a tomato with the right taste that people
love,'' said Harry Janes, who has conducted greenhouse tomato
research at Rutgers since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Rutgers scientists also can grow tomatoes closer together
than farmers can on fields. About 150 pounds of tomatoes can grow
in 90 days on a 6-by-15-foot greenhouse table, about five times as
many as farmers can grow in the same area in a field.
</P>
<P>
   ''I prefer the tomatoes grown outside, but in the wintertime,
when you can't enjoy a nice Jersey tomato, (the greenhouse
tomatoes) are not a bad tomato to have,'' said Al Murray, chief of
market development and promotions for the state Agriculture
Department's Division of Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Janes said the university is close to developing a plan for
farmers to use the greenhouse research to grow tomatoes for more
months of the year. Tomatoes are now harvested between July and
October. California and Florida export most of the tomato crops
during winter months.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are just about to the point now where we can demonstrate
profitability for farmers,'' Janes told The Star-Ledger of Newark
in Monday's editions. ''We're not there yet, but each year we're
getting closer and closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the greenhouse tomatoes, labeled with white and green
stickers that say ''Jersey Fresh Premium Greenhouse Tomato,''
always exceeds supply at supermarkets that have sold them over the
last three years, said Jeff Shilling, director for purchasing for
RLB Food Distributors, which sells the greenhouse tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers have been wary of the greenhouse method because of cost.
Building a greenhouse can cost tens to hundreds of thousands of
dollars. Many said they would consider trying to grow a Jersey
tomato indoors if costs could be contained.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have recommended using fuel from a nearby source to
power the greenhouse. In Columbus, Rutgers scientists use energy
generated from the waste at the adjacent Burlington County
landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Matarazzo, a Warren County farmer and member of the New
Jersey Tomato Council, says energy costs may keep farmers from
trying to grow tomatoes in winter.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fuel prices are definitely going to deter most farmers from
going into the dead of winter with greenhouse tomatoes,'' Matarazzo
said. ''But extending the season, say through March and April and
May, and November and December, that would be great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
