<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serial killer sentenced to life in prison  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) - Kendall Francois was sentenced to life
in prison without parole Monday for the murders of eight women
whose bodies were found in his family's home.
</P>
<P>
   Francois, 29, made no statement and looked down or straight
ahead as members of the victims' families spoke in Dutchess County
Court. His attorney said that Francois was deeply sorry for his
actions, but did not want to give a statement that could be
misconstrued by the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to see you die eight times over,'' said Heidi
Cramer, whose mother, 51-year-old Sandra French was killed by
Francois. The former middle school hall monitor had confessed to
all eight murders to avoid the death penalty. He told police that
he had solicited the women for sex and then strangled them.
</P>
<P>
   His family members were not implicated in the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Sala escaped from Francois and called police on Sept.
1, 1998, leading authorities to the gruesome discovery of the
bodies in Francois' garbage-strewn home.
</P>
<P>
   The murders occurred over a 22-month period from October 1996 to
August 1998. ''If I had the chance, I'd cut you up into little
bitty pieces,'' Sala said. ''I hope they kill you in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois, who has tested positive for the virus which causes
AIDS, was also sentenced to eight consecutive sentences of
25-years-to-life and 1 1/3 to four years for attempted assault on
Sala.
</P>
<P>
   Dutchess County Court Judge Thomas J. Dolan told Francois that
he had caused anguish to an entire community with his ''unspeakable
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois' cousin, MonRay Francois, sat with victims' family
members in the courtroom, but did not speak Monday. He has said in
the past that he believed his cousin should get the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Dutchess County District Attorney William Grady had
said he would seek the death penalty, but said in June that he
accepted the plea bargain in part because of the victims' families
who wanted closure and a guarantee that Francois would die in
prison. In addition, Grady had said the Francois' psychiatric
issues would weigh heavily in a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Francois and his lawyer had tried to thwart Grady's intention to
seek the death penalty immediately after Francois' arrest by having
him hurriedly plead guilty to the slayings in December 1998. That
was before the 120-day period had expired under which Grady and
other prosecutors have to decide whether to seek the death penalty
against a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   In May 2000, the state's highest court, the Court of Appeals,
ruled that no plea is valid in a death penalty case while a local
prosecutor is weighing whether to seek to execute the defendant.
</P>
</TEXT>
