<HEADLINE> U.S. Calls for Release of Ibrahim  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department urged Egypt on Monday to
free a respected Egyptian-American liberal sociologist who has been
imprisoned for a month without being charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Richard Boucher said ''it's a fair assumption'' that
Saad Eddin Ibrahim, 61, is in jail because of his advocacy for
human rights in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Under Egyptian law, Ibrahim can be held up to six months without
formal charges. Other members of his research group, Ibn Khaldun,
which monitors working conditions, also have been detained, Boucher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have made several accusations against Ibrahim in
their investigations, including that he accepted foreign money
without government permission and forged voting cards for a
documentary about elections that tarnished Egypt's image. Ibrahim
has denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim's lawyer, Farid el-Dib, told The Associated Press on
Sunday that the scholar also was accused of ''espionage for the
United States to undermine Egypt's national security and harm its
military, economic and political interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher, asked about the situation at Monday's State Department
news briefing, said, ''We share the concern of many others who
question the detention of an internationally recognized advocate of
civil society and democratic reform in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the reported espionage accusation, U.S. diplomats who
met in Cairo with senior Egyptian officials were told that no
charges were filed against Ibrahim, Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   ''So we're pleased to find that those reports (of espionage
allegations) are inaccurate,'' Boucher said. ''But we remain deeply
concerned about his continued detention without charges. The
Egyptian government is fully aware of our concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing Ibrahim's extended detention inexplicable, the U.S.
spokesman said, ''We call upon the Egyptian government to make
clear the formal charges against him or, better yet, to release
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
