<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murderer of former police officer sentenced to 22 years to life in prison </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A drug abuser who stabbed a retired New York
City policeman to death with a 10-inch bayonet while arguing with
the victim's daughter was sentenced Monday to 22 years to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Bruce Allen told Thomas Kelly, 48,
that he imposed less than the maximum of 25 years to life because
he did not believe his murder of William Hageman, 51, was
premeditated. ''The criminal intent was formed almost on the spur
of the moment,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   A Manhattan jury convicted Kelly of second-degree murder on May
8 for fatally stabbing Hageman in the chest on July 29, 1997,
outside a Lower Eastside tenement building, where the former cop
was the superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   An unconscious Hageman was taken to nearby Beth Israel Medical
Center where he was pronounced dead a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   A letter from the youngest of Hageman's two daughters, Kristin,
now 14, was read in court by Assistant District Attorney Kevin
Pogue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never felt pain like this before,'' Kristin wrote. ''Each
time I think about him (Hageman), something inside me dies because
I know I'll never get to tell him I love him ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   Offered a chance to speak before he was sentenced, Kelly said,
''I'm just sorry that it happened. What else can I say? There's no
more to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Pogue told the court that Kelly had waited outside the apartment
house and stabbed Hageman after futilely pleading to get Hageman's
daughter, Dawn, 29, to move back in with him. She refused. They had
lived together for 3&AMP;frac12; years.
</P>
<P>
   Hageman rebuffed Kelly saying did not want to hear anything he
had to say, and told him to leave his family alone.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Kelly stabbed Hageman and fled, trial evidence
showed.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Kenneth Walsh asked Allen to impose the minimum
sentence. He said Kelly was a hard working man who developed a drug
addiction and who was turning his life around and trying to get his
ex-lover to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said Kelly's intent during the confrontation was ''to
rescue Dawn from a downward spiral.'' He never intended to hurt
anyone, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Hageman became a police officer in 1968. He retired in 1977
while assigned to the Central Park Precinct. He had been working as
the superintendent in the East 12th Street building for 17 years
when he was killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
