<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $adv12  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Heading from east to west, here are some of U.S.
Route 20's many
highlights:
<TEXT>
<P>
   -The first formal Shaker Society settlement in America was
started in the Mount Lebanon area.
</P>
<P>
   -The oldest unaltered Episcopal church in the state, built in
1789, is located in Duanesburg.
</P>
<P>
   - In Sharon Springs, the derelict shells of once-majestic hotels
still stand as a silent reminder of the days when tourists came by
the thousands to bath in the area's natural sulfur and magnesium
springs.
</P>
<P>
   -Cherry Valley was the scene of a famous massacre in 1778 in
which nearly 50 villagers and soldiers were killed by raiders led
by Joseph Brant, a prominent Iroquois chief. A large marble
sarcophagus commemorates the attack.
</P>
<P>
   -Richfield Springs is the home of the Petrified Creatures Museum
of Natural History, chartered in 1934 as one of the oldest hands-on
museums in the state. Visitors can dig for 40 different kinds of
invertebrate fossils on the museum's nearly six acres, which also
include woodland trails, nature paths and life-size dinosaur
statutes.
</P>
<P>
   -In Sangerfield, travelers pass the northern tip of Nine Mile
Swamp, which once served as the hiding place for the infamous
Loomis Gang, which terrorized the countryside from 1848-1866.
</P>
<P>
   -Bouckville, where one of the largest antique shows in the
Eastern United States is staged every August. Nearby is Nichols
Pond, where Samuel de Champlain and an expeditionary force of
French and Hurons attacked a stockaded fort of the Oneida Indians
in October, 1615 - an act that helped drive the Iroquois tribes to
ally with the English during the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   -Cazenovia was a stagecoach stopover where John Lincklaen built
the Lorenzo House in 1807, an exquisite two-story Georgian
structure that features delicate pilasters, elliptical arches,
gables and a roof parapet.
</P>
<P>
   -Between Pompey and Lafayette, travelers cross the heart of the
ancient Onondaga Indian Nation where the centuries-old Iroquois
Confederacy was born. The area also is one of the leading
apple-producing areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
   -In Cardiff, visitors will learn the history of the Cardiff
Giant, a 10-foot tall hand-carved statute that was buried in the
ground by two 19th-century local hucksters and became regarded as
''America's Greatest Hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   -As travelers pass through Auburn, they can stop at the homes of
Harriet Tubman, who became a national heroine for her pivotal role
in leading slaves to freedom through the Underground Railroad, and
former Secretary of State William H. Seward, who engineered the
purchase of Alaska from Russia in 1867.
</P>
<P>
   -Montezuma Swamp, a national wildlife refuge and a birdwatchers'
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   -In Seneca Falls, the birthplace of the women's suffrage
movement where visitors can stop at the National Women's Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   -Waterloo boasts it is the birthplace of the first Memorial Day
observance. It also is the location of the Scythe Tree. Legend says
that in 1861, James Wyburn Johnson, a local farm boy, hung his
scythe on a six-inch poplar sapling until his return from the Civil
War. Johnson was killed in battle and scythe remained while the
tree grew. Today, today only six inches of blade shows; the wooden
handle having long ago rotted away.
</P>
<P>
   -Geneva is the home of the acclaimed Lake Geneva Inn and the
site of an old Iroquois village. It lies in the heart of the Finger
Lakes region and New York's world famous wine country.
</P>
<P>
   -Town Line is remembered for the fact that a majority of the
townsfolk voted in 1861 to join the South and seceded from the
Union.
</P>
<P>
   -After passing through the Cattaraugus Indian Reservation,
travelers come to Westfield, the original headquarters of the Welch
Grape Juice Company, started in 1896 by Dr. Thomas Branwell Welch
and his son.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Preservation League of New York, American Guide
Series: New York
</P>
<P>
   END ADVANCE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-07-00 1658 </TRAILER>
