<HEADLINE> US Blasts Chavez for Iraq Visit  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department reacted sharply Monday to
the planned visit of Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez to Iraq and
vowed an effort to persuade him to cancel it.
</P>
<P>
   The Thursday visit to Baghdad will be the first by a foreign
head of government since United Nations sanctions were imposed
against Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said it was
''particularly galling'' that the first such visit is being made by
a leader who is democratically elected. For Chavez, he said, this
is a ''dubious distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela and Iraq are both major oil exporters, and Chavez will
visit Baghdad as part of a tour of Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries. He arrived Monday in Saudi Arabia, his first
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said it is hard to understand Chavez's decision to visit
Iraq, given what he called Iraq's ''continuous flouting of its
international obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Iraq remains unwilling to accept U.N. Security Council
demands requiring the country to relinquish its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be discussing President Chavez' plans to visit Baghdad
with relevant officials in Venezuela in an effort to find some
other means to accomplish his goal of coordination with the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States is also concerned about reports that
Chavez would go to Baghdad without the required United Nations
approval
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Venezuela's obligation, as a U.N. member state, to
observe all the Security Council resolutions regarding Iraq and the
sanctions regime,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   While expressing concern privately about Chavez's links to Cuba
and his commitment to democracy, the Clinton administration has not
criticized him because he generally has followed democratic norms,
including national elections on July 30 in which Chavez was awarded
a six-year term by a comfortable margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan leader has made a point of staking out an
independent foreign policy -- forging a close friendship with Cuba's
Fidel Castro and praising Libya as a model of ''participatory
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's trip to 10 oil-producing nations is part of Chavez's
stated goal of strengthening the oil cartel as a global force.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez plans to invite his OPEC counterparts to a Sept. 27
summit in Venezuela, the first such meeting since 1975.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Library of Congress country notes:
http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/cshome.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
