<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Struggles To Free Its Money  </HEADLINE>
By CLAR NI CHONGHAILE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Lawyers for the cash-strapped Russian Embassy asked
a French court on Monday to unfreeze its bank accounts, the latest
chapter of a bizarre legal feud that has left the mission
struggling to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   Pitted against Russia is a Swiss-based trading company, Noga,
which says Moscow owes it $62.5 million from oil-for-food deals
signed in 1991, the year the Soviet Union dissolved, and in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Noga managed to get the accounts of Russia's embassy, trade
mission and delegation to UNESCO frozen in May. The accounts hold
only $392,000, but the lack of resources is starting to pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ''An embassy without a bank account cannot work,'' Daniel Guyot,
a lawyer for the Russian side, said after the court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Noga's claim was backed by an arbitration court in Stockholm,
Sweden, in 1997, clearing the way for the legal action in France.
Lawyers for both sides pleaded their cases at Monday's hearing at
the Court of Appeals. The verdict is due Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The case has taken its toll on already strained relations
between Russia and France, a vociferous critic of Russia's war in
the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Noga has not just targeted Russia's diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, it succeeded in temporarily impounding a renowned
Russian tall ship that sailed to France to take part in an
international regatta.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss firm also threatened to seize Russian President
Vladimir Putin's plane when he comes to France on an official visit
set for October.
</P>
<P>
   The court battle centered on whether Russia, at the time still
part of the Soviet Union, signed away its immunity from payment
default in the original contract, and whether that included
diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Noga contends it did, making all Russia's assets fair game in
its bid to recoup its money. Noga lawyer Antoine Chatain said it
was pursuing legal claims in Luxembourg, Switzerland and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the appeal, Guyot told the court that Russia's
diplomatic immunity was protected by the Vienna conventions of 1961
and 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we were to accept the senseless theory supported by Noga,
it would allow a private company to close an embassy, which is
unheard-of in the international community,'' Guyot told reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 1710 </TRAILER>
