<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McGreevey gets backing from Torricelli's home base  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Bergen County Democrats staged yet another
rally Monday to back Jim McGreevey for a gubernatorial race that is
more than a year away.
</P>
<P>
   This one was held on the home turf of U.S. Sen. Robert
Torricelli, who recently dropped his brief bid to challenge
McGreevey for the Democratic gubernatorial nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli backed out after leading state Democrats came out in
support of McGreevey earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   But Torricelli still hasn't offered McGreevey his support.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen county Democrats deny that the rally, which was held just
days after a similar event held in Trenton, was designed to put the
pressure on the powerful senator to throw his weight behind
McGreevey.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ferriero, county chairman, said he would like to see
Torricelli endorse McGreevey, but the rally was aimed at
discouraging anyone else from challenging the Woodbridge mayor for
the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to send a very strong and powerful message to anyone
else who might be thinking about running for governor that Bergen
is united solidly behind Jim McGreevey,'' Ferriero said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, 16 county chairmen, representing nearly 75 percent of
the state's Democrats, crammed into a room at the Statehouse,
gathered around McGreevey and called for the party to unify behind
him for the 2001 gubernatorial election.
</P>
<P>
   Rich McGrath, Torricelli's spokesman, said the senator supports
Democratic leaders making their own decision about whom to endorse
- and he'll do the same when the time is right.
</P>
<P>
   ''Democratic leaders must reach their own individual decisions
about endorsing candidates,'' McGrath said. ''Just as Senator
Torricelli will use his best judgment when and how to best help the
Democrats of New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey and Torricelli met recently for the first time since
Torricelli announced his candidacy and then backed out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a positive and friendly meeting that demonstrates that
their friendship and mutual respect are strong and more enduring
than any temporary political competition,'' McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said Torricelli is focusing right now on national races
and has no timetable for making a decision about New Jersey's 2001
gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's rally was touted as the largest political endorsement
ever in Bergen County.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ferriero, state Sen. Byron Baer, D-Bergen,
Assemblyman Ken Zisa, D-Bergen, all 27 Bergen County Democratic
mayors and a raft of other party leaders were among the supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jim McGreevey has worked with the rank and file here in Bergen
County for years,'' Ferriero said in a telephone interview. ''There
has always been this closeness with him. It was unfortunate that we
had to take a step back when Bob (Torricelli) was contemplating a
run. With that behind us, everyone is extremely enthusiastic about
Jim's candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians reportedly contemplating a run at earning the
Democratic gubernatorial nomination are: U.S Reps. Robert Andrews
of Haddon Heights, Frank Pallone Jr. of Long Branch and Bill
Pascrell of Paterson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
