<HEADLINE> Clinton's Dog a Splash at Beach  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- Buddy, President Clinton's dog, made
quite a splash at the beach and beyond on the first family's
whirlwind weekend vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The sleek chocolate Labrador retriever ate ice cream, met the
locals and played rough with Clinton in the waves.
</P>
<P>
   ''Buddy and I went swimming'' Sunday, Clinton told reporters.
''He clawed me pretty bad,'' the president said matter-of-factly as
he patted his upper chest gingerly.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got in some rough waves. I should have given him a manicure
before we went out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, as Clinton greeted people in the town of Vineyard
Haven, Buddy tolerated a sea of hands reaching under a rope
barricade to pat him, and stood, panting, as one delighted family
took a picture with him.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy's reward for patience was a goodly portion of Clinton's
double-dip raspberry and peaches and cream ice cream cone. Clinton,
emerging from Mad Martha's ice cream shop with daughter Chelsea,
tossed the treat to Buddy, who downed it in one gulp.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gotta share,'' Clinton said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy, who has accompanied the Clintons on several trips to
Martha's Vineyard, was honored with his own T-shirt in this final
year of the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Vineyard bakery and gift shop The Black Dog printed
a version of its standard logo shirt featuring a Labrador wearing
an Uncle Sam top hat and playing the saxophone. On the back it
reads: ''Hail and Farewell. Here's to Wonderful Vineyard Memories.
Bye-bye, Buddy. Bye-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons spent three days on Martha's Vineyard this year,
their shortest vacation on the island yet.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds swarm Buddy almost as eagerly as they greet the
president, and years of star treatment seem to have made the dog
blase. Although polite, Buddy shows little interest in anyone other
than Clinton and a White House steward who serves as the dog's
primary handler.
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, interested in food. When allowed to roam the
White House West Wing unfettered, Buddy makes a single-minded
circuit of staff offices and the press room. A quick check of the
trash can, a sniff of the carpet for crumbs and he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy may be the only White House resident who thoroughly
enjoyed last month's Camp David peace talks. For him, the rural
setting and loose schedule were ideal: Lots of room to run and lots
of people eating at almost any hour of the day or night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
