<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Several injured in I-91 accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORWICH, Vt. (AP) - Wet pavement is being blamed for an accident
that sent a van airborne off the southbound lane of Interstate 91
in Norwich.
</P>
<P>
   Four children and two adults, all from New York, were
transported to the Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center in Lebanon,
N.H., by several ambulances from the towns of Fairlee, Hartford and
Hanover, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont State Police Trooper Peter Garivaltis said none of the
injuries sustained in the accident appeared to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looked a lot worse than it was. There was a ton of
ambulances up there because there were four kids in the van and
everyone was being really cautious because of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The occupants of the van were all family members from Brooklyn,
N.Y., and the four children were ages 1, 2, 3, and 5, Garivaltis
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The little ones are all fine,'' he said. ''They were just
bringing the father in for some precautionary x-rays, but everybody
else was set to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Garivaltis said the cause of the crash appeared to be the wet
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The driver said the road was wet and he just slipped off the
road. There wasn't any skidding on the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Norwich Fire Chief Jack Fraser, who oversaw the rescue efforts,
said crews worked quickly to help the injured but were hampered by
a language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were all Korean and as near as we could tell none of them
could speak English,'' he said. ''We went down into the brook bed
and searched all around to make sure there weren't any more
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the ambulance crews and a large number of Vermont
State Police troopers, fire engines and FAST Squad members were
called to the scene from Norwich, Hartford, Thetford and Hanover to
provide manpower to help carry patients on backboards several
hundred feet back up to the roadway for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It takes a while to evaluate each patient and get them
properly on the backboard and check them out so it took awhile,''
Fraser said. ''We put five people in neck braces and stuff because
we weren't sure how bad they were.''
</P>
<P>
   The van was headed south and had just passed over the
Pompanoosuc Bridge when the accident occurred shortly before 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The van ended up upright in a stream with both front airbags
deployed and some damage to the bottom and the front of the
vehicle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
