<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman on ticket could help Hillary Clinton win Jews  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - He stood up for Hillary Rodham Clinton when she
was accused of anti-Semitism, and he stood next to her when she met
with Orthodox rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   Now Joseph Lieberman's name will appear along with Clinton's on
every ballot in New York. And that could help her get Jewish votes
she desperately needs to beat Republican Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary has got to be smiling today,'' said Democratic state
Assemblyman Dov Hikind, an Orthodox Jew who has not yet made an
endorsement in the Senate race and has criticized Clinton for some
of her positions on Jewish issues.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore selected Lieberman, the Democratic senator from
Connecticut, as his vice presidential running mate Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Someone like Lieberman, who is deeply respected, is going to
make a lot of independent-minded people take a second look at the
Democrats,'' Hikind said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly, it's good news for Hillary,'' said Lee Miringoff,
pollster for the Marist Institute for Public Opinion. ''She's
having trouble with the Jewish vote. This will start off a larger
number of Jews on the Gore-Lieberman-Clinton line. ... Also we can
expect a larger Jewish turnout. It's not a guarantee of success but
it shifts everything to a more favorable terrain for her.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If they project a close race for Hillary, as they are
projecting, it could be the difference,'' said U.S. Housing
Secretary Andrew Cuomo, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show voters overall are nearly evenly divided between
Clinton and Lazio. Jews make up just 12 percent of the electorate
here, but about 15 percent of them are undecided, so winning their
support could help win the race.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has also been fighting a perception that she is
overly sympathetic to the Palestinians, and Lieberman could aid her
credibility. In December, he accompanied Clinton to a meeting with
the Orthodox Union, which represents Orthodox synagogues. Last
month, Lieberman joined other Jewish legislators in Washington
defending Clinton against an allegation that she used an
anti-Semitic obscenity in an argument in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's friendship with the Clintons goes back to 1970, when
President Clinton - then a Yale Law student - campaigned for
Lieberman's state Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, New York Democrats were already gleefully
linking the first lady's name with his. ''Al Gore, Joe Lieberman,
and Hillary Clinton will be a strong and effective team,'' said
state party Chairwoman Judith Hope.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks Clinton will get a bounce from
Lieberman's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Yaakov Kornreich, who works for the National Council of Young
Israel, which is based in New York and represents 150 Orthodox
synagogues nationwide, noted that Lieberman is best known for
having denounced the president's sexual escapades and said, ''If we
see the selection of Joe Lieberman as a repudiation of the Clinton
White House, I don't see how that helps Hillary Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Diament, public policy director for the Orthodox Union,
said that if Lieberman were to campaign with Clinton, ''maybe that
could impress some swing voters.''
</P>
<P>
   But he pointed out that ''if Lazio and Clinton get in a debate
about school choice, Lazio can say, 'Well, Sen. Lieberman voted for
school choice.''' Lieberman supports tax-funded vouchers for
private school tuition; Clinton does not. Lazio supports them in
areas with failing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign spokesman Dan McLagan said that while Lieberman
is ''well-respected on both sides of the political aisle, I doubt
it'll have any impact on the Senate race because New Yorkers
realize this is about Hillary Clinton and Rick Lazio, not who Al
Gore's V.P. pick is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
