<HEADLINE> Taiwan President to Stop in L.A.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite China's objection, the president of
Taiwan will be permitted to stop in Los Angeles on his way to
Central America later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement is designed ''for the safety and convenience of
the traveler,'' the State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
Monday. ''There are no meetings expected with any administration
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   China objected to the U.S. decision to issue Chen Shui-bian a
visa for the layover in Los Angeles and warned it would damage U.S.
ties with China severely.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao expressed ''strong
resentment and firm opposition'' to the decision.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, China was enraged when Chen's predecessor, Lee
Teng-hui, was permitted to speak at his alma mater, Cornell
University. China responded by lobbing test missiles near Taiwan
and suspending talks with the island.
</P>
<P>
   Chen announced last month that he would visit Taiwan's allies in
Central America and Africa in August, via Los Angeles, in his first
diplomatic offensive since taking office in May.
</P>
<P>
   The two-week trip, beginning Sunday, includes Dominica,
Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Gambia, Burkina Faso and Chad, which are
among Taiwan's 29 diplomatic allies.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing China's complaint, Boucher said ''We have explained
it to the Chinese. I think we've answered this question several
times in public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
