<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuomo, Pataki dole out federal grants  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo and
Gov. George Pataki Monday went on separate grant-giving trips in
eastern New York, but both said their handing out of government
goodies on the same day was just a scheduling coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Cuomo is considering a run for governor in 2002 while
Pataki, a Republican who unseated Cuomo's father Mario in 1994, has
indicated he may seek re-election to a third term in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo stopped at Haverstraw, Peekskill and Beacon to announce
$19.4 million in federal economic development funds for the Hudson
Valley region. Grants were awarded to the three communities, as
well as to Ossining, Yonkers, Newburgh and Poughkeepsie.
</P>
<P>
   The funds are part of a regional economic development plan
modeled after HUD's Canal Corridor Initiative for communities along
the Erie Canal, Cuomo spokeswoman Sandi Abadinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson River Partnership 2000 comprises the seven
communities and is expected to create more than 500 jobs locally,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said the Erie Canal was ''an overwhelming success'' and
that the Hudson Valley Partnership would ''bring the same concept
to sustainable economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pataki doled out more than $22 million in federal
money for various local projects in eastern New York. The governor
stopped in Highland Falls, Scotia and Saranac Lake to make the
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Development Block Grant Small Cities Program was
originally administered by HUD, but last year President Clinton
authorized transferring control of the program to the Pataki
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The transition ended weeks of political squabbling in Albany and
Washington over who would get authority - and thus the political
credit - or handing out the $60 million in federal grants. Prior to
Clinton's action, New York and Hawaii were the only states that
didn't distribute the federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York communities now deal with one central office that is
accountable to New York residents,'' Pataki said. ''This is a major
improvement over the previous Washington-based process.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said Monday the funds are still HUD money, with ''the
state as our agent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I appreciate Governor Pataki highlighting the importance of
the federal grants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republicans have said they were concerned about the
political mileage Cuomo could have gotten out of the grant program
during a possible gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Pataki and Cuomo said they were not aware of each
other's schedules until Monday, when it became apparent that the
two men were making announcements similar in nature.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our schedule was made way in advance,'' Cuomo spokeswoman
Sandi Abadinsky said. ''It's a coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokeswoman Suzanne Morris also called the competing
grant-giving tours a ''coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Abadinsky said the funds Cuomo handed out Monday came out of
federal programs that were separate from the Small Cities
initiative.
</P>
<P>
   About $15.8 million of the assistance came from HUD's Economic
Development Loan Guarantees, which allow municipalities to borrow
money at reduced interest rates. The remaining $3.8 million are
grants from the federal Economic Development Initiative, designed
to help create local jobs among low and moderate income residents.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Cuomo released a report Monday touting the
economic impact of the Canal Corridor Initiative. The Cornell
University study concluded that the initiative helped increase
hotel occupancy and boat traffic in the region and would result in
27,000 new jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
