<HEADLINE> Giuliani: City had record number of visitors in 1999  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The number of tourists visiting the city reached
an all-time high in 1999, with 36.7 million visitors spending an
estimated $15.5 billion, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is second only to Orlando as the destination of
choice among visitors from the United States, according to the
convention and tourism bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism figures - culled from the U.S. Department of
Commerce, consumer surveys and a travel research study - were not
debated by tourism officials in Orlando or Las Vegas, which placed
third, according to the city report.
</P>
<P>
   The convention and tourism bureau defines a visitor as someone
who travels at least 50 miles to reach the city - excluding
commuters - or someone who stays overnight.
</P>
</TEXT>
