<HEADLINE> Congressional colleagues support Gore's choice  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA TOMMELLEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The five Democrats and two Republicans in
the Connecticut congressional delegation have tackled everything
from defense contracts to heating oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, they reacted with pride and praise after learning
Sen. Joseph Lieberman is Vice President Al Gore's choice for
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a proud day, a wonderful day for the state and the
country. You have two very bright, committed individuals who will
make their case across the country,'' said U.S. Rep. Rosa DeLauro,
a New Haven Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   DeLauro, who has known Lieberman for about 30 years, said she
also believes voters will sense the genuine friendship between Gore
and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't feign a friendship,'' said the five-term
congresswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Senate colleague Christopher Dodd called his fellow Democrat ''a
tremendously decent human being.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he thinks Lieberman should continue his re-election
bid for Senate. Under state law he can run for both at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a strong candidate. I don't think it's fair to deprive
him of that,'' said Dodd.
</P>
<P>
   John Larson, the first-term Democrat from East Hartford, said he
believed Gore's choice had more to do with who Lieberman is than an
attempt to distance himself from President Clinton's sex scandals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think he selected Joe Lieberman to get inoculated,''
said Larson. ''As we know ... (Lieberman's) a fighter, he's willing
to take on big oil, the pharmaceutical industry, the entertainment
industry. ... I believe that that's the reason that Gore selected
him.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. James Maloney, a Waterbury Democrat, said Lieberman's
candidacy would energize voters from all parties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe Lieberman is a man of strong character and family
values,'' said Maloney.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Sam Gejdenson said Lieberman would be a solid
campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really strengthens Al Gore and builds the kind of
partnership we want in the White House,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican colleagues also praised Gore's choice. U.S. Rep.
Christopher Shays of Bridgeport likened Lieberman to Bush running
mate Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is thoughtful and articulate, and commands respect on both
sides of the aisle,'' said Shays.
</P>
<P>
   New Britain Republican Rep. Nancy Johnson also praised
Lieberman's ability to work across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore has done himself a great favor. He couldn't have made
a better choice,'' Johnson said. ''I think it strengthens the Gore
ticket, but in the end I never saw any presidential election that
was determined by the vice presidential nominee.''
</P>
</TEXT>
