<HEADLINE> Democrats, Jews, even Whitman shower praise on Lieberman selection  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Al Gore is drawing praise in New Jersey for
his choice of a running mate both from Democrats counting on a
solid presidential ticket and from Jews proud that a milestone has
been reached in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, is
expected to formally introduce Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman
Tuesday at a Tennessee news conference. Lieberman, a devout
Orthodox Jew, confirmed to reporters Monday he had been offered and
had accepted the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Even Republican Gov. Christie Whitman offered a backhanded
compliment Monday, saying Lieberman would fit better with GOP
presidential nominee George W. Bush because of Lieberman's
integrity and support for school-choice programs. ''Sen. Lieberman
has been more in synch with Gov. Bush than he's been with Vice
President Gore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg said Lieberman boosts the ticket as a
man of high morals who will place education first. But Lautenberg
downplayed the importance of the nominee's religious faith, noting
he and Lieberman are among 11 Jews in the U.S. Senate. ''I think
once we've had a couple of days go by, you'll see less talk that
he's a Jew,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac College of Hamden, Conn., reported that its polling
in New Jersey since June 1999 found Lieberman with higher approval
ratings among New Jersey registered voters than another other
person they asked about. The most recent poll on July 20 gave
Lieberman a 74-percent approval rating in a poll with a margin of
error of 3.1 percentage points. Five earlier polls gave Lieberman
approval ratings above 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Goldstein of the Anti-Defamation League called the
selection ''a milestone in America's political maturity and
sophistication.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be an even greater milestone if his Judiasm had no
impact either way,'' Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The senator is an observant Jew who has served his state well
for 12 years, so it should not matter,'' Goldstein said, doubting
there will be a measurable loss of votes because of anti-Semitism.
''These people will be dismissed as the extremists that they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Loretta Weinberg, D-Bergen, praised Lieberman's
selection as a triple play because it appeals to her as a party
organizer in New Jersey, as a delegate to the Democratic National
Convention and as a Jewish woman.
</P>
<P>
   ''On all three of those counts I am very, very pleased with this
selection,'' she said. ''It came as a surprise, which by itself is
very important to boost interest in the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg recalled how her father, Murray Isaacs, endured
anti-Semitic insults while involved in Democratic politics in New
York City. ''As a Jew, this will be a moment none of us ever
forgets,'' she said. ''This country is a little bit behind on
firsts.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.algore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.georgewbush.com
</P>
</TEXT>
