<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina's Unemployed Pray  </HEADLINE>
By BILL CORMIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Tens of thousands of Argentina's
unemployed and under-employed flocked to a shrine of the patron
saint of labor on Monday, in an annual pilgrimage swollen by one of
the highest jobless rates in years.
</P>
<P>
   Waving sheaves of grain symbolizing work, the crowd formed lines
winding their way more than a mile to the Church of San Cayetano, a
Roman Catholic saint many here call upon in times of joblessness.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God, I now have work. I am here to thank San Cayetano
for fulfilling my prayers,'' said Oscar Gomez, a 36-year-old
carpenter who went three months without a job and now counts
himself lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrimage, held every year on Aug. 7, comes just weeks
after the government of President Fernando De la Rua announced the
official unemployment rate remains stubbornly high.
</P>
<P>
   The government reported in mid-July that national joblessness
has edged up to 15.4 percent. That compares with 13.8 percent in
October.
</P>
<P>
   The latest unemployment figure is still lower than the peak of
18.4 percent reached in May 1995, but it has left many analysts
with darkened hopes for an economic revival in Argentina. The
country is struggling to pull itself from a region-wide recession
that began in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now, the unemployed have been camping around the San
Cayetano church in hopes of an economic miracle, some traveling
from poorer cities in the Argentine countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no work. I need to find work to take care of my son.
I'll do anything: clean rooms, work as a maid, anything,'' said
Maria Fernandez, 25, who cradled an 8-month-old boy in her arms.
</P>
<P>
   Police cordoned off whole blocks around the church, and street
vendors spent a brisk morning selling plastic statues of San
Cayetano and special powders and incense used in petitions to the
labor saint.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Alegre, 44, brought his two children in tow, hoping for
work. ''It's been a year since I've had a decent job. Right now I'm
just doing any little thing to get by,'' said Alegre. ''This has
been a very tough year.''
</P>
<P>
   Double-digit unemployment has troubled Argentine since 1994 --
even during periods of high growth. The government has forecast 3.5
percent growth this year, but independent economists say that is
optimistic at best.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Molina, a 25-year-old restaurant worker, said Monday he
was thankful for his job, but worried about the rest of Argentina.
''Things are rally bad. You can see it in the streets,'' said
Molina.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of job seekers have lined up in recent weeks at
factories and businesses advertising only a handful of jobs.
Protests by unemployed workers have become commonplace in
Argentina's impoverished provinces, where demonstrations often
ended in clashes with police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
