<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox: US Ties May Help Latin America  </HEADLINE>
By EDUARDO GALLARDO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Mexico's President-elect Vicente Fox said
Monday his country's close trade and economic ties with the United
States could help bring stronger ties with Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In the Chilean capital, Fox launched a four-nation tour of South
America vowing to seek ''full integration.'' Aside from Chile, Fox
will visit Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay, which along with Paraguay
make up the Mercosur free trade block.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to make absolutely clear that we are turning our eyes
toward Latin America,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a joint news conference with Chilean President
Ricardo Lagos, Fox said the United States should drop its current
unilateral certification of foreign countries' efforts against drug
production and trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said his trip -- his first since his July 2 election victory
-- aims to show that while ''we have built a very important trade
and political relationship with North America, that should not
separate us from Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, he said, ''our closeness to the world's biggest
market should be useful to every nation in Latin America.'' Mexico
formed the North American Free Trade Accord, NAFTA, with the United
States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said the certification of efforts against drugs by countries
that produce drugs or are used as transit by traffickers ''should
be a multilateral mechanism where we all participate, with clearly
established obligations and goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the United States makes a unilateral certification,
which is also used to determine its aid to foreign nations.
</P>
<P>
   A multilateral action ''would allow us to face in an
internationally coordinated manner a crime that is internationally
organized,'' Fox said. ''It is not possible for individual
countries to fight this scum, this cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who takes office Dec. 1st, said his government will
maintain Mexico's oil giant ''in the current conditions'' under
state ownership. He said private investments will be accepted in
some areas of the electric sector, but that the sector would remain
in the hands of the state.
</P>
<P>
   He said that as a result of his election, Mexico has gained
''full democracy.'' Fox was the first opposition presidential
candidate to defeat a member of Mexico's ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, in power for 71 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
