<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani administration orders safety changes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The Giuliani administration has ordered a series
of safety measures at one of the city's largest parades after two
children and an adult were struck and killed last year by floats.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes at next month's West Indian American Day
Parade will be a ban on alcohol sales and consumption, and the
requirement that the parade's drivers and vehicles pass a Police
Department safety review before the September 4 parade.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the city will mandate vehicles pulling floats to have a
police officer riding in the passenger cab and require the parade's
marshals to undergo training by the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations, recommended by a mayoral task force, will
also be instituted at the city's other parades.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1999 West Indian Day Parade, two 11-year-old children
dancing behind a parade float died after the truck pulling the
float stopped abruptly and a second vehicle pinned them between the
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the vehicle that stopped had a suspended license.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, an 18-year-old man was killed by a float
after he was startled by someone in the crowd with a yellow snake
and stumbled backward. His clothing became caught on the float - an
18-wheel flatbed truck - and he was pulled under it and crushed.
</P>
<P>
   But City Councilwoman Una Clarke said the city ban on alcohol
sales at related events preceding the parade could hurt the event's
finances, which is underwritten in part through alcohol sales
during the five-day celebration that encompasses the parade.
</P>
<P>
   The annual parade in Brooklyn attracts some 2 million people
each year and has been a New York tradition since the 1930s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
