<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYPD reports 56 incidents during first two days of strike  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Strikers heckled workers at Verizon
Communications buildings on Monday and police reported 56 incidents
of violence or harassment during the first two days of a phone
company strike affecting 87,200 workers in 12 states.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 picketers wearing red union T-shirts milled about
behind police barricades in front of the company's midtown
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hey scab! How's it feel to be a scab!'' they shouted at people
who entered and left the building.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want job security,'' said Jeff Greenberg, a central office
technician and shop steward. ''Everything we've worked for in every
contract Verizon is trying to re-negotiate and retrogress.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Rodriguez, a customer service representative, added,
''They're relocating our work. We can do it. Why go to outside
contractors?''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between Verizon and its unions - the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers - continued Monday in Washington after the contract expired
early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The main issues include job security and the unions' ability to
organize in Verizon's wireless division, where fewer than 50 of the
32,000 workers are union members.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon was formed in June by the merger of Bell Atlantic and
GTE Corp and maintains 160 offices, garages and warehouses
throughout the five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   New York City police reported 40 acts of vandalism against phone
company installations since Sunday and 16 other incidents such as
threats against Verizon managers.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,500 telephone customers lost service in the Bronx on
Sunday, and in Manhattan someone vandalized a fiber optic station
on East 15th Street, causing another 600 customers to lose phone
service.
</P>
<P>
   A Verizon truck was set on fire in the Bronx on Monday but
firefighters quickly extinguished the blaze, said Sgt. Brian Burke,
a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Soraya Rodriguez, a Verizon spokeswoman, said the company was
''not making assumptions'' about who was responsible for the acts
of vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's part of doing business, unfortunately,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Master, a spokesman for the union, said, ''We discourage any
illegal behavior, we discourage any acts of violence, but we are a
militant union and we organize and protest very forcefully.''
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as we know, there is no indication that this is even
connected to the strike. Even the company admits that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said some 30,000 managers have been deployed to keep
phone service running.
</P>
<P>
   ''Customers should have no problems making or receiving calls,''
she said, but adding that anyone who calls for repair work should
expect delays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
