<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman praises American dream, working people, attacks Republicans </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Suddenly in the spotlight as Al Gore's
running mate, Joseph I. Lieberman praised the American dream and
told Connecticut union workers that they are the engine of the
economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Officially wearing the hat of a senator seeking re-election,
Lieberman spoke Monday to the state AFL-CIO political convention.
But word of Gore's early morning decision turned the speech into a
rousing rally for the 58-year-old Orthodox Jew from New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, a funny thing happened to me on the way to the
AFL-CIO convention,'' Lieberman joked as hundreds of union workers
chanted his name.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't think of a place I'd rather be at this momentous time
in my life than with you, the working people of the state of
Connecticut,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore formally gave Lieberman the vice presidential nod in a
telephone call at midday, and Lieberman accepted, having known for
hours that the job was his.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, Lieberman emphasized his working-class
beginnings and they way his own parents lived the American dream.
He praised both teachers and laborers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is you and your families that are the real heroes in making
Connecticut's comeback happen,'' he said. ''You are the engine that
has driven our remarkable economic recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on all levels have successfully created jobs, lowered
interest rates, protected the environment and helped Americans move
from welfare to work, Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Gore, Lieberman described his boss-to-be as an
honorable, intelligent, hardworking man who is qualified to lead
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will be proud to stand with him every day, just as I am
proud to stand with you, the true American heroes.'' Lieberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   His words for the Republican party were less friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the working people of America look for a helping hand
from the other party and the other ticket, they too often will
receive the back of the hand,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, as reporters awaited Lieberman's arrival outside the
Hartford Hilton, his Republican opponent in the Senate race took
the stage. Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano said his city has a
strong, longtime association with labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano said he walked picket lines with union workers after a
local mall was built by non-labor workers. His most notable
achievement regarding unions in Waterbury, he said, has been the
development of strong project labor agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've done my best to maintain a good relationship with the
unions,'' he said. ''The local trade unions have an excellent
record of completing a quality job on time, and under budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite speculation that Republican leaders may ask him to
withdraw from the Senate race in favor of a stronger candidate,
Giordano said he is not quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't give up the ship that easy,'' Giordano said. ''It's
the old Marine in me. Once I make a decision, I give it 150
percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
