<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blumenthal: Lieberman started trend of activist AGs  </HEADLINE>
By RICH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Before he was a U.S. senator, before he
was Al Gore's running mate, Joseph Lieberman was Connecticut's
attorney general. While in that office he went after consumer fraud
and polluters with a vigor that sent the tone for his successors.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was one of the first proactive, really activist attorneys
general, particularly in areas like consumer protection and
environmental safeguards,'' said current Attorney General Richard
Blumenthal, also a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said Lieberman took on unsafe products such as lead
paint and certain types of all-terrain vehicles; targeted home
improvement fraud and odometer tampering; and brought hundreds of
lawsuits alleging violations of air, land, and water pollution
laws.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1985, Lieberman threatened to sue record stores that
keep profits from ''Do They Know It's Christmas,'' a British album
meant to benefit starving people in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later he went to bat for then-state Rep. Chris
Shays, a Republican, who had been jailed for refusing to halt a
statement from the witness stand criticizing the state's judicial
review procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman argued that Shays should not have been jailed during
the legislative session and challenged the constitutionality of
Superior Court Judge Norris L. O'Neill's contempt ruling. The case
was later ruled moot.
</P>
<P>
   Shays is now a Republican member of Congress from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1985 Lieberman lost a U.S. Supreme Court case in which
he defended the state's sabbath law, which required employers to
give workers their choice of a day off for religious purposes each
week. The high court struck down the law as violating the
separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 Lieberman failed in an effort to force the Boy Scouts of
America to accept a female troop leader, and sued the USA for
Africa Foundation for failing to file a required financial
disclosure statement.
</P>
<P>
   USA for Africa, maker of the ''We Are the World'' rock music
video, had raised millions of dollars, mostly for famine relief
victims in Africa. Lieberman dropped the suit after getting the
information he sought.
</P>
<P>
   ''In terms of environmental law and consumer protection, he was
very much at the forefront nationally in many different cases,''
Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly, the very activist and aggressive approach to using
the law was different,'' he said. ''He made a very significant mark
on the office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-07-00 1917 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
