<HEADLINE> To friends and neighbors, Lieberman will always be 'Joe'  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Joseph Lieberman's life was catapulted
into the national spotlight Monday, but those who know the vice
presidential candidate say his new and temporary title won't change
him or what they think of him.
</P>
<P>
   When news broke that Al Gore had chosen Lieberman as his running
mate, friends and neighbors joined the growing crowd of reporters
in front of the Connecticut senator's house in the upper
middle-class Westville neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Some were holding congratulatory signs reading ''Mazel tov
Joe.'' A next-door neighbor shouted ''Go get 'em Joe!'' when
Lieberman crossed his driveway on the way to take a private jet to
Gore's campaign headquarters in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has remained very humble,'' said Rabbi Albert Feldman of
the Westville Synagogue, which Lieberman attends. ''When he comes
to the synagogue, he still takes his seat in the back. And to
everyone, he's Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   Even last Friday - after a long meeting earlier in the day with
Gore - Lieberman wasn't too preoccupied to join his neighbors
across the street at sunset to usher in the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ''We asked him if he would accept the nomination to join us,''
joked Nachama Langenauer, Lieberman's neighbor for the last 22
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very exciting, but we just know him as a person,''
Langenauer said. ''Who would think the person across the street
would be running for vice president?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Segaloff, who was a law firm partner with Lieberman from
1973 to 1985, said his friend was always more interested on
politics than law.
</P>
<P>
   ''At one level this doesn't surprise me,'' Segaloff said of
Lieberman's rise from state senator to attorney general and U.S.
senator. ''He was always very focused and very together. He had an
incredibly strong moral commitment to do what was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Many say it's Lieberman's strong moral center that made him a
good pick for Gore, who critics charge is poised to inherit a
morally bankrupt administration.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was one of the first Democrats to criticize President
Clinton's behavior in the Monica Lewinsky scandal, and has been a
vocal critic of violence and sex in movies and on television.
Beyond his neighborhood, Lieberman's sense of decency has gained
respect in his workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe Lieberman is a giant in the Senate,'' said Massachusetts
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy. ''He's worked brilliantly, effectively and
tirelessly to promote the highest values of public service and
integrity in public office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
