<HEADLINE> Ferre: Wallet Stolen at Funeral  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONCE, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Former Gov. Luis A. Ferre says a
pickpocket stole his wallet with $1,500 during a funeral for his
sister, a Roman Catholic nun whose charity work gained her acclaim
in Puerto Rico and the U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Ferre, 96, told police that the wallet disappeared Saturday
during a ceremony attended by thousands of people for Isolina Ferre
in Ponce, according to a police report. Ferre was escorted by aides
and police bodyguards at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Monday they had no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Ferre founded the U.S. Caribbean territory's New Progressive
Party and was governor from 1968 to 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Isolina Ferre, founded centers for delinquent youth in
Puerto Rico, New York and the Appalachian mountain region of the
United States. She was awarded her the Medal of Freedom, the United
States' highest civilian honor, in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
