<HEADLINE> Titans' McNair Rests Sore Shoulder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Steve McNair watched practice Monday
afternoon, resting his sore shoulder following the Tennessee
Titans' exhibition opener.
</P>
<P>
   McNair finished practice with some light running, and coach Jeff
Fisher said the quarterback will be back at practice Tuesday.
Fisher said coaches didn't want to push McNair so early since the
Titans don't play again until Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just sore. He's actually been stiff last week, week and a
half, and just worked through it. He's been doing an awful lot of
throwing. We just decided to back down a little bit,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher said the soreness wasn't a concern even though McNair
sat out some drills during a practice last week. McNair was 3-of-5
for 26 yards and a touchdown in the Titans' 14-10 victory over
Kansas City on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans did get linebacker Terry Killens (strained quad
muscle) and cornerbacks Dainon Sidney (strained calf) and Kareem
Clark (hamstring) back at practice.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Yancey Thigpen ran by himself during drills and spent
25 minutes catching passes from rookie quarterback Billy Volek
after practice. The Titans hope he can join in drills for the first
time since training camp started by mid-week.
</P>
</TEXT>
