<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colts' Bennett Passes Physical  </HEADLINE>
By HANK LOWENKRON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TERRE HAUTE, Ind. (AP) -- An anxious Cornelius Bennett went to
bed early Sunday night -- hoping he would pass his physical the next
morning and get to practice with the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   The good night's sleep paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Normally, I stay up until two, three o'clock in the morning,
regardless of what time I have to get up,'' he said. ''I was in bed
about 8, 8:30.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very anxious to get out to prove, not only to everybody
that wants me out there, but to prove to myself that I can overcome
adversity,'' said Bennett, who led the Colts with 114 tackles last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's plans for a 14th NFL season were put on hold when he
failed a physical after reporting to training camp July 13. He had
remained in camp, rehabilitating his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett injured two ligaments in his knee on the opening play in
the final regular season game. He has missed only 10 regular season
games due to injury in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a long road from January 2,'' Bennett said. ''It was
hard work on my behalf, and the trainers, and a lot of praying --
and here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who will be 35 on Aug. 25, was a major part of a
defense that helped the Colts win the AFC East last year with a
13-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   Since camp opened, he's mainly been a spectator on the field,
watching and offering help to the team's young linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be out there, but then it's the preseason. In my
mind, training camp is training camp,'' he said. ''I've worked real
hard. ... To come back from the injuries that I had is very
unrealistic in a sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett didn't need surgery to repair his medial collateral and
posterior cruciate ligaments, but the injury left the Colts in dire
need of experienced linebackers. That need became greater as
first-round draft pick Rob Morris missed 17 practices during his
contract holdout and second-round pick Marcus Washington missed
most of the camp with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett has too much football savvy to rush himself back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't do all the practice today. I stayed out of the
contact work. Overall, I thought I had a pretty good first day,''
he said, adding he has no plans to play when the Colts meet New
Orleans in West Lafayette on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went through the individual drills. I still got some rust,
but I think that just might be old age,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was injured on the opening weekend of camp and missed
24 practices until returning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was good to be out there with the guys, just to get back in
the swing of things,'' said the rookie from Auburn, who is expected
to be a back up to Bennett and also play some defensive end this
season. ''It (watching) was kind of hard to be because I'm kind of
used to going full speed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
