<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Military in Disappearances  </HEADLINE>
By RICARDO MIRANDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- A report by a leading human rights group
about children who vanished during Guatemala's civil war says the
military was to blame for most of the disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Roman Catholic Church's main human rights
office in Guatemala, released to the media on Monday, details the
cases of 86 children who disappeared during the 36-year civil war,
which ended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The military said it would not respond until it saw the report.
</P>
<P>
   ''The military has not seen this document, and we would have to
read it carefully before giving our point of view,'' said the
office of military spokesman Capt. Jose Maria Valladares.
</P>
<P>
   The report's authors said there are accounts of 358 other cases
that could not be fully documented.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims were members of Guatemala's Maya Indian
majority, who suffered most from the army's scorched-earth campaign
against rebel fighters, the report said. Hundreds of villages were
raided and many were obliterated.
</P>
<P>
   In the vast majority of disappearances, the children were
abducted, said Nery Rodenas, director of the Archbishop's Human
Rights Office. The rest were caused by ''the dynamic of armed
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have in our hands is the confirmation that children
were used as war booty, that forced disappearance was used as an
instrument of war against those most vulnerable, the children,''
Rodenas told a news conference. In some cases, the vanished
children ''were used for military ends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which will be released publicly Tuesday, attributed
79 of the cases to the military, 3 of the cases to
government-organized paramilitary groups and 2 of the cases to
leftist rebels. The causes of 2 of the cases could not be
clarified.
</P>
<P>
   One case highlighted in the report was that of Baudilio Monzon,
a 9-year-old Mayan boy who vanished on Feb. 18, 1984 during a raid
on his village.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, a military helicopter dropped fliers with a
picture of the boy in a hospital bed and message promising safety
if villagers came out of the jungle where they had fled and
surrendered to the army. ''Thank God, I am being healed,'' the
flier quoted the boy as saying.
</P>
<P>
   His parents have not seen him since. The boy's father was quoted
in the report saying he had heard at first that his son was being
kept at a military unit in Xalbal, about 180 miles north of the
capital, then years later that he was under the care of a colonel
named Castillo.
</P>
<P>
   Rodenas said many of the families lack the resources to search
for the children. ''Furthermore, there is still fear of reprisals,
which leads them to leave things as they are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the next step is to try to locate the missing children
and try to reunite them with their families.
</P>
<P>
   The coordinator of the human rights office, Bishop Mario Rios
Montt, urged Guatemalans to confront the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let it not be a political issue nor a motive for profit or
sensationalism,'' he said. ''Remember that it involves human beings
who have been profoundly harmed by war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 1951 </TRAILER>
