<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Members of Congress walk trail, try mediating dispute  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARRISON, N.Y. (AP) - Sen. Charles Schumer and Rep. Sue Kelly
walked a short stretch of the Appalachian Trail on Monday to see
for themselves the forested land that the National Park Service
wants and a Franciscan friary doesn't want to give up.
</P>
<P>
   And after listening briefly to officials from both sides, they
expressed confidence about a compromise and announced that
negotiations would begin Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been misunderstandings about what each side really
wants,'' Schumer said. ''The two goals are not in conflict. We
don't need to take this to court.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2,500-mile trail, which runs from Georgia to Maine, crosses
Graymoor, headquarters of the Franciscan Friars of the Atonement,
along a 58-acre easement the park service purchased in 1984. But in
some places the easement is only 50 feet wide and the park service
wants to buffer it with an additional 18 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The friars, who are among the trail's most hospitable hosts -
they offer food and shelter to all hikers - are wary of losing a
bigger piece of their ''Holy Mountain'' and want to retain room to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the park service - which has seen the friary
violate the easement with a pump house and sewer pipes - wants to
eliminate the possibility of development a backpack's throw from
the trail.
</P>
<P>
   After years of on-and-off negotiations, the park service
referred the case to the Justice Department this spring for eminent
domain proceedings - taking the land without permission while
paying market price.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, a Republican, called that ''a heavy-handed tactic.'' She
and Schumer wrote to Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and the park
service agreed to hold off, pending negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The elected officials met Monday with the Rev. Arthur Johnson,
minister general of the friars; Pam Underhill, the trail
superintendent for the park service; and Judy Brumbach, the
service's chief of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very amicable and very productive,'' said Underhill.
''We have each other's attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added, ''I am sure something can be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said various general ideas about settlements were
discussed, but added, ''The devil is in the details.'' He would not
specify what form any agreement might take.
</P>
<P>
   ''God and nature are one to some of the great Catholic and other
philosophers,'' he said. ''The goals of both parties are in no
conflict whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said there was no discussion of money because, ''That is
not our concern.''
</P>
<P>
   On the trail, Schumer marveled at the beauty of the forest,
steamy in near-90-degree heat. ''This is not Brooklyn,'' said the
Democrat from Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But the hikers also noted a manhole cover labeled ''sewer'' and
Underhill said, ''You don't see too many of these on the
Appalachian Trail.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
