<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, Aug. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore's VP Pick Is Lieberman
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore today selected Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman
to be his running mate, rounding out the Democratic ticket with the first Jewish
vice presidential candidate for a major party in American history. Gore offered
the spot on the ticket in a telephone call and Lieberman accepted. ''That was
the call. It was directly from Al Gore,'' Lieberman said, pulling up to his
house in New Haven, Conn., with a cell phone to his ear. ''We said a short
prayer together,'' the senator said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GOP Convention TV Ratings Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Average viewership on ABC, CBS and NBC during George W.
Bush's four-night Republican nomination process was 16.1 million, down 3 percent
from the GOP convention that nominated Bob Dole in 1996, according to Nielsen
Media Research. Non-broadcast networks that covered the 1996 convention also
said their ratings had slipped this year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Netscape Bug Affects Almost 1,000
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Security experts were warning Internet users today about a
flaw in Netscape's Web browser that has already infected almost 1,000 computers.
Once a computer is infected, a hacker can see, run and delete files on the
target computer.''Netscape takes all security issues very seriously,'' said
Netscape spokesman Andrew Weinstein, ''We're working to quickly evaluate and
address this concern.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nuke Sites May Not Rid Contaminants
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than two-thirds of the government sites involved in
decades of nuclear bomb production will never be completely cleaned of
contamination, according to a study by the National Academy of Sciences.
''Long-term stewardship will be required for over 100 of the 144 waste sites,''
said the report released Monday by a special panel examining government plans to
deal with this legacy of the Cold War years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
104 Arrested in D.C. Protest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON(AP) -- Police arrested 104 people today as they sat down in front
of the White House to protest the decade-old international sanctions against
Iraq. Many of the 250 demonstrators at the White House and Treasury Department
chanted ''stop the killing of Iraqi children.'' Some held aloft loaves of bread
and others held signs reading ''Iraqi children Holocaust II'' and ''remember
Iraq.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Verizon Talks Go On Despite Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talks between Verizon Communications, the Northeast's
leading local telephone company, and striking union members hit a snag today
over several issues, including the shifting of work to areas that are not as
heavily unionized or where the pay scale is lower. The strike by some 87,200
company employees affected operations for 25 million customers from Maine to
Virginia. Verizon was formed from the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Scientists Find Nine New Planets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Astronomers said today they have found nine new planets
circling stars outside our solar system -- evidence that the Earth and its
neighbors may not be as special as we like to think. Three teams of researchers
from Switzerland and the United States told a meeting of the International
Astronomical Union about the discoveries.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Premature Kids Linked to Problems
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Babies born prematurely tend to have more problems in
school and in childhood socializing than do babies that were carried to full
term, according to a new study. The study, by psychology researchers at Syracuse
University, found that significantly more children born prematurely had
behavioral, learning and thinking problems than did children who were born full
term. The study was presented today at the national convention of the American
Psychological Association.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
More Deaths May Be Linked to Tires
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration is now
investigating 46 fatalities it believes could be linked to failing Firestone
tires, more than double the number it had tallied last week. NHTSA spokeswoman
Liz Neblett said as of today the agency had received more than 270 complaints
about failing Firestone truck tires -- the vast majority of them installed on
Ford Explorer sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 99; Nasdaq Gains 76
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rallied today on optimism that interest rates will
remain stable following data that suggests the economy is slowing. The Dow Jones
industrial average closed up 99.26 at 10,867.01. On the NYSE, gainers led losers
1,713-1,135. The Nasdaq was up 75.63 at 3,862.99.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mariners Beat Yankees
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Carlos Guillen hit his first career grand slam today as the
Seattle Mariners beat the New York Yankees 8-5. Seattle's John Halama (10-5)
allowed three solo homers -- two to David Justice -- but little else. Also, the
Yanks got Jose Canseco on waivers from Tampa Bay.
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER 
</P>
