<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Leader Visits Saudis  </HEADLINE>
By ABDULLAH AL-SHIHRI
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Saudi Arabia and Venezuela are
intent on ensuring a stable oil market with a goal of an average
oil price of $25 a barrel, officials said Tuesday after Venezuelan
President Hugo Chavez opened a tour of OPEC nations.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez met late Monday with Saudi King Fahd and Crown Prince
Abdullah in the Red Sea port city of Jiddah. The visit comes
against a backdrop of warnings of an oil price collapse and of
quota-busting among members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   No official statements followed the meeting, which ended early
Tuesday. A Venezuelan source, however, said afterward that the two
sides agreed the current OPEC production level is sufficient so
there is no need for additional supplies this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The source, who insisted on not being further identified, didn't
say whether the sufficient level included some or all of the extra
500,000 barrels a day the Saudis had decided to add to the market
to bring down prices, of which about 200,000 barrels a day is
estimated to be on the market now. The Saudi plan had angered many
of its OPEC partners.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez and Saudi leaders, the source said, also agreed that high
prices in large industrialized nations were mainly due to high
taxes on oil or oil products but were being blamed on producing
nations.
</P>
<P>
   A Saudi official, who also insisted on anonymity, said the
leaders also discussed the need for coordination between OPEC and
non-OPEC nations to maintain stability in oil markets ''with a goal
of an average price of $25 a barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Fahd told his Cabinet that both countries are
keen in maintaining oil market stability and balance for the
interest of all producers and consumers. ''Our views are identical
on a number of petroleum issues,'' the official Saudi Press Agency
quoted Fahd as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's trip is aimed at welding unity among OPEC members and
comes one week after OPEC president and Venezuelan Oil Minister Ali
Rodriguez expressed concern over reports that the organization is
leaking an extra 700,000 barrels a day into the market.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC delivers about one-third of the world's oil supply. Its
official output is 25.4 million barrels a day. Saudi Arabia, the
cartel's most influential member, produces almost a third of that.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela, once the group's most notorious quota buster and most
apathetic member, has been lobbying for stability in the market
through establishing closer ties with fellow OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela was instrumental in engineering production cuts after
oil prices hit record lows in 1998 and 1999, lifting prices to
9-year highs and earning Chavez credibility among OPEC countries.
</P>
<P>
   During his tour, Chavez was extending invitations to the leaders
of Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, United Arab Emirates, Iran, Iraq,
Indonesia, Libya, Nigeria and Algeria to attend an OPEC summit in
Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's tour is also significant because he will visit Iraq
next week, making him the first foreign leader to pay an official
state visit to Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department sharply criticized Chavez for the
planned stop in Baghdad, calling it ''particularly galling'' that
the first such visit is being made by a leader who is
democratically elected.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Richard Boucher said the United States is also
concerned about reports that Chavez would go to Baghdad without the
required United Nations approval. ''It's Venezuela's obligation, as
a U.N. member state, to observe all the Security Council
resolutions regarding Iraq and the sanctions regime,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2102 </TRAILER>
