<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angels Release Pitcher Ken Hill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Right-hander Ken Hill, in the final
season of a $16.05 million, three-year contract, was released
Monday by the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, 34, was 5-7 with a 6.52 ERA in 16 games this season -- all
starts. He spent three weeks on the disabled list earlier this
season and only last week admitted to contemplating retirement
because of an arthritic elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not disappointed, because I'd been thinking of hanging it
up anyway,'' Hill said before the Angels played the Boston Red Sox.
''I'd rather go out on a more positive note than getting
released.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim manager Mike Scioscia said releasing Hill was difficult
because of the effort the right-hander had put into regaining his
form.
</P>
<P>
   ''But he just wasn't responding to the needs we had,'' Scioscia
said. ''The consistency we sought just wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill's release -- and the trade a week ago of Kent Bottenfield --
leaves Anaheim dependent on a young starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels began Monday night's game in third place in the AL
West, 8&AMP;frac12; games behind Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand that they need innings, and they've got young
guys they need to see,'' Hill said. ''They want to see them
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, which is responsible for the remainder of Hill's $5.6
million salary, activated left-hander Jarrod Washburn to take
Hill's place on the roster. Washburn, 6-2 with a 3.87 ERA, was
scheduled to start Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the rotation includes rookies Scott Schoeneweis and
Brian Cooper, with Matt Wise, another rookie, expected to make his
first major league start Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Another rookie starter, Seth Etherton, was placed on the
disabled list Sunday with a tired arm.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was acquired by the Angels from Texas for catcher Jim
Leyritz and infielder Robert Sasser on July 29, 1997, and re-signed
with the Angels the following November. The Angels had a $6 million
club option for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just didn't think Kenny pitched as well as he could, or
take as deep into games as we expected,'' Anaheim general manager
Bill Stoneman said. ''It's an opportunity for one of our young
pitchers to be in the rotation, and I don't think that's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who spent time on the disabled list earlier this season,
had a 4-11 record with a 4.77 ERA in 22 starts and four relief
appearances last season. He was 9-6 with a 4.98 ERA in 19 games in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hill also spent time with the St. Louis Cardinals, Montreal
Expos and Cleveland Indians. His career record is 117-107 with 19
complete games, eight shutouts and a 4.00 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2104 </TRAILER>
