<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Royals' Beltran Begin Rehabbing  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG TUCKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Outfielder Carlos Beltran has begun
working out in Kansas City and remains suspended without pay for
refusing to go to Florida on a rehab assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, saying it was team policy, told Beltran to work out
at their spring training complex near Haines City, Fla. Beltran
objected, citing a clause in baseball's collective bargaining
agreement, and the Royals said last Thursday they were suspended
him without pay for 30 days or until he reported to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The players' association then filed a grievance, forcing the
matter before arbitrator Shaym Das. The union also said it will
file a default notice if Beltran doesn't get a full paycheck Aug.
15.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Allard Baird said he met with Beltran on Monday
and that nothing had changed with the 1999 AL Rookie of the Year,
who went on the DL on July 5.
</P>
<P>
   Beltran will rehab his bruised right knee at Kauffman Stadium
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where we are right now is Carlos is going to continue his
rehab program here,'' Baird said. ''We've set it up with our
trainers and our strength and conditioning guys as well as our
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird said this does not mean the Royals have made a concession
to Beltran.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't scrapped the policy. We've suspended the player,''
he said. ''I'm not going to tell a 23-year-old kid to go out and
swing off the tee on his own. I'm not going to tell a 23-year-old
kid to go out and rehab himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltran does not appear to have much sympathy from his
teammates, many of who have done rehab work at the Florida complex.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got better things to worry about,'' third baseman Joe
Randa said. ''We've got to focus all our concentration on trying to
win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltran said Monday he wants ''the team to accept me when I'm
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to be away from the team. That's what I don't
think they understand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The switch-hitting Beltran was batting just .247 with six home
runs and 32 RBIs following a terrific rookie season, when he hit
.293 with 112 runs scored, 22 home runs and 108 RBIs. Getting him
physically ready to play by Sept. 1 would be ''cutting it close,''
Baird said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our discussion today was on a personal level, not a business
level,'' Baird said. ''We're talking about a very young kid who
came off a tremendous year last year and has failed a little bit
this year. I'm sure he has second-guessed himself in a lot of
different things on the field. And now he's put in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is there compassion from me? Yes. Who's the most important in
this thing? The organization. We had a good discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird does not expect the arbitration hearing to be held until
late August. If the union files a default notice, the Royals said
they will pay Beltran the full bimonthly portion of his $350,000
salary rather than risk him becoming a free agent if Das rules in
his favor.
</P>
<P>
   If the Royals win the grievance, the money would be withheld
from later paychecks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000807.0128 </DOCNO>
