<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressRobin Day:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Sir Robin Day, a combative and witty broadcast
journalist who changed the face of political interviewing in
Britain, died Sunday after being admitted to hospital for heart
tests. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Day, famed for his spotted bow ties, was best known for his role
as presenter of the popular BBC television current affairs debate
''Question Time'' featuring a panel of politicians and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Day joined the BBC in 1959 and led ''Question Time'' from 1979
to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by two sons.
Jack Edelstein:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jack Edelstein, a longtime statistician for
the Philadelphia Eagles who was master of double talk and once
dated Marilyn Monroe, died Friday of liver cancer. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein was famous for his nonsensical speeches at roasts and
charity events. He also did his routine at serious symposiums.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein dated Hollywood stars, befriended politicians and
millionaires and hung out with comedians Don Rickles and Jerry
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   He kept stats for the Eagles for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein was born in Philadelphia and attended Temple
University. He was a Navy pilot in World War II and was shot down
three times.
John Hohenberg:
</P>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Former journalism professor, author and
Pulitzer Prize administrator John Hohenberg died Sunday of colon
cancer. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   A New York City native, Hohenberg worked as a reporter, editor,
foreign correspondent and Washington correspondent for several New
York newspapers and United Press before becoming a journalism
teacher at Columbia University, his alma mater, in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure at Columbia, Hohenberg also served as
secretary of the advisory board and administrator of the Pulitzer
Prize from 1954 to 1976.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote 11 books on journalism, two of which were
anthologies of Pulitzer winners.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a son and a daughter.
Carlos Ortiz:
</P>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) -- The Rev. Carlos Ortiz Sr., a charismatic
minister who said he wanted to preach to every Hispanic in the
world via television, died Saturday night from an apparent heart
attack. He was 56.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a Bible and a pack of satellites, Ortiz exported
bilingual Christian television programs to Latin America, Spain and
West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Puerto Rico and raised in New York, Ortiz worked as a
long-haul trucker until 1973, when he said he found Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   After working 15 years as an evangelist, the former street gang
member moved to the Rio Grande Valley and founded Faith Pleases God
Church. He later started La Familia Television Network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2112 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000807.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stottlemyre Recovering Quickly  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Todd Stottlemyre's recovery from an elbow injury
is ahead of schedule and the Arizona Diamondbacks have tentatively
targeted his return to the rotation for Sept. 3 against the Florida
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander has been on the disabled list since June 26
with tendinitis in his right elbow. He plans to begin throwing off
the mound on Wednesday, about five days ahead of what had been
scheduled, after a week of throwing on flat ground each day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm fired up,'' Stottlemyre said Monday. ''I've thrown seven
straight days and I've had no pain. I have felt great every day.
It's kind of nice to stand here and be honest with you and tell you
I feel good when I really feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   If Stottlemyre can return for the stretch run, he would add to
an already formidable rotation that includes Randy Johnson, Curt
Schilling and Brian Anderson. The Sept. 3 date looks good to
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do I think I can make it?'' Stottlemyre said. ''Book it.''
</P>
<P>
   Team doctor David Zeman gave his blessing to the accelerated
schedule, which would include a couple of rehabilitation
appearances in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's looking better than I had anticipated,'' Zeman said.
''He's just doing great. ... His strength is great. His shoulder's
looking great. His flexibility is really good. He just looks really
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre already is pitching with a partial tear in his
rotator cuff. That injury last season required extensive
conditioning as he decided to come back without surgery,
compensating for the tear by beefing up the muscle around the
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He came back to earn Arizona's lone victory in its playoff
series against the New York Mets last fall, then got off to a
strong start this season. In 14 starts, he was 8-5 with a 4.24 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   But the tendinitis first sidelined him on May 14. He returned on
June 14, and initially pitched without any problems. Then the pain
returned, worse than ever, and doctors prescribed a much longer
layoff.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee the pain won't return, Zeman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why we want to go cautiously,'' the doctor said. ''But
in terms of all the ways of measuring it -- tenderness, swelling,
range of motion, strength, flexibility. All the objective things
look great. And I think this time Todd understands that he can't
tolerate a setback. He's not going to rush it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre is expected to undergo elbow surgery after the
season.
</P>
<P>
   But he wants to come back for the tough September schedule that
faces the Diamondbacks as they try to defend their NL West title.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to push because I feel good,'' Stottlemyre said.
''If there's anyway I can help, I'm going to try to help. At this
point, I'm not going to get overly crazy about it because there's a
long road between now and a major league start.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I guess from a long-term standpoint, the nice thing is
it's not like I'm going to go out there and put my whole career at
risk where I couldn't come back next year. That's not the case.
Knowing that, knowing the structure of my elbow is in good shape,
if I have to pitch in some sort of pain, so be it. I did it the
first two months, I can do it the last two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
