<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strike continues, some consumer services delayed  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Talks between Verizon Communications, the
Northeast's leading local telephone company, and striking union
members hit a snag Monday over several issues, including the
shifting of work to areas that are not as heavily unionized or
where the pay scale is lower.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, the Communications Workers of America,
the larger of the two unions in negotiations, said several
job-security issues have slowed the overall progress of contract
talks although discussions continued Monday evening. The strike by
87,200 company employees affects operations for 25 million
customers from Maine to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators wrapped up the day's formal talks around 8 p.m. EDT.
They expected to begin talking again Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the barriers to a settlement is the question of
transfer of work. Verizon was formed in June by the merger of Bell
Atlantic and GTE Corp., and unions fear the company could move work
to areas that are cheaper or have less of a union presence or force
employees to relocate.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it needs flexibility to distribute calls
depending on the level of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue bogging down talks deals with a subsidiary of
Verizon that handles wiring within the home, the CWA said. That
division split off from the main business several years ago so that
it could have a separate wage scale and compete more effectively
with rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The unions argue that some of the work done by this subsidiary
in five states and D.C. should really be handled by workers in the
core company.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues still unresolved include organizing rights for
wireless workers, forced overtime and workplace stress.
</P>
<P>
   But Verizon spokesman Eric Rabe said he was not discouraged by
the bumps because the two sides are continuing to discuss these
issues.
</P>
<P>
   The strike affects these areas in Verizon's territory: Delaware,
the District of Columbia, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New
Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island,
Vermont, Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company, 14,000 employees picketed in front of
Verizon facilities Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Spellane, spokesman for the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, which is also at the bargaining table, said
that 800 other IBEW members - who work for a Verizon subsidiary but
are not part of these talks - filed an unfair practice complaint
with the National Labor Relations Board against the company Monday,
</P>
<P>
   The workers allege that when they refused to cross CWA picket
lines in New Jersey where they work, the company took disciplinary
action against them, Spellane said. The workers then went out on
strike, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, police reported 56 incidents of violence or
harassment and 40 acts of vandalism against phone company
installations since Sunday - when the strike began.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 Verizon managers filled in for the more than 87,000
striking employees, pledging to work 12-hour shifts and focusing on
critical network repairs first.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said they did not think the strike would harm
the phone system's integrity, but weather conditions could cause
outages. Verizon also recommended that consumers hold off on
ordering new phone lines or asking billing questions until the
strike ends.
</P>
<P>
   In Providence, R.I., more than 350 people rallied outside the
local headquarters. Workers wore black T-shirts with a cobra rising
from the union symbol on the back and the slogan, ''Will strike if
provoked.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There doesn't seem to be any loyalty to workers,'' said John
Lang, 52, of Johnston, R.I., a technician for 32 years. ''All we
want is a few crumbs from the table and don't give our jobs away.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sensitive issue at the bargaining table is the unions'
ability to organize in Verizon's burgeoning wireless division -
where fewer than 50 of the 32,000 workers are union members.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders say they want to ensure that their members can get
access to jobs in the wireless division, framing it as a question
of labor's presence in the new economy. The union also is pushing
for a system in which employees in that unit could vote for
representation by filling out an authorization card.
</P>
<P>
   The company says ballot elections would protect workers' rights
better. On Monday, Verizon officials bristled at the idea that
union members don't already have access to high-tech jobs. They
contended the company has experienced tremendous growth in its data
business, which provides high-speed Internet service over its
traditional phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''The objective is for us to add high-tech new economy jobs
there,'' said Rabe, the company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com/home.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-07-00 2130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
