<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Virginia company agrees to buy Millstone to $1.3 billion  </HEADLINE>
	   By DONNA TOMMELLEO:
Associated Press Writer:
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A Virginia power company will buy the
Millstone Power Station from Northeast Utilities for $1.3 billion,
the companies announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the once-troubled nuclear complex to Dominion
Resources Inc. is expected to be completed by April 2001 and must
still undergo regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dominion will be a welcome new competitor in the state,'' said
Michael Morris, NU chairman and chief executive officer. ''We are
extremely pleased that our Millstone nuclear units are being sold
to an outstanding company committed to operating a safe and
successful national nuclear organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlin-based Northeast Utilities, planning a merger with
Consolidated Edison of New York to create the nation's largest
electric and gas distribution company, put the three-plant complex
on the auction block several months ago to comply with deregulation
laws requiring it to divest power generating units. The company
also has sold its fossil fuel plants in New England.
</P>
<P>
   The complex was sold through a bidding process handled by J.P.
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   The final price was so far above the $240 million minimum bid,
the sale will save Connecticut consumers about $1 billion in the
so-called stranded costs, said state utility regulators. NU needs
to collect those costs from customers to cover debts incurred under
decades of regulation. The higher the price of the plant, the lower
the stranded costs will be.
</P>
<P>
   The Richmond-based Dominion has been lauded by industry analysts
and federal regulators for its safety record and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have an excellent track record and some of the most
efficient plants in the country,'' said Paul Patterson, an analyst
from Credit Suisse First Boston. ''They're a first-rate nuclear
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of a Safe Millstone also welcomed the sale to Dominion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dominion Resources is nationally known for its zeal for safety
and its passion for first-rate environmentally sensitive nuclear
operations,'' said Ron McKeown, director and founder of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear Regulatory Commission spokesman Roger Hannah, whose
Region 2 office oversees Dominion, said former NRC Chairwoman
Shirley Jackson would often hold Dominion up as an example of how a
company can be both efficient and safety conscious.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a management team from Dominion assisted NU about three
years ago while Millstone was shut down due to safety concerns.
That's when the interest in the complex along the Long Island Sound
shore began.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought the equipment was good. We felt the people there
were very good,'' said James O'Hanlon, president and chief
operating officer of Dominion's generation subsidary. ''When NU
changed the management and the leadership it all started coming
together. Plus, those folks up there know how to work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Millstone was shut down four years ago and had to undergo
intense NRC scrutiny until federal regulators were convinced the
company improved its safety procedures and handling of
whistleblower complaints. Millstone 3 reopened in June 1998 and
Millstone 2 restarted last May. Millstone 1 is in the process of
being decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process they went through when they were shut down was
probably one of the most intensive efforts seen in this country,''
said NRC spokesman Neil Sheehan. ''We've seen some dramatic
improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   Millstone employs about 1,800 people. NU spokesman Joe
Pillittere said all workers have been guaranteed a job at least one
year after the sale is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal since recovering has been to become the best of the
best and this agreement really reinforces that goal and places
Millstone in an environment that fully supports safety and
efficiency,'' said Pillittere.
</P>
<P>
   Dominion, which operates two nuclear plants in Virgina, serves
about 4 million customers in Virginia, North Carolina, Ohio,
Pennsylvania and West Virginia. NU has 1.75 million customers in
Connecticut, New Hampshire and Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-07-00 2144 </TRAILER>
