<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Mudslide Victims Remembered  </HEADLINE>
By JAY LINDSAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTON, Mass. (AP) -- A father and son who died in a freak
mudslide in Switzerland over the weekend were remembered Monday as
devoted people who made family a top priority even after a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vaughn and his son, Benjamin, were killed Sunday while
walking with a group of 18 hikers and two guides across a flat
trail above the central Swiss resort of Grindelwald. The Vaughns
were buried when the sudden mudslide swept them 66 feet downslope
into a mountain stream.
</P>
<P>
   After Paul Vaughn divorced his wife, he moved next door to her
and her parents, and friends said the neighborhood scenario
illustrated where Vaughn placed his priorities. The arrangement
ensured both he and his ex-wife could easily raise their children
together as parents, if no longer as spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of amazing,'' said Richard Toelke, Vaughn's
colleague and friend. ''After his divorce, he probably wanted to
move away from his wife. ... But whatever was best for his kids,
that's what was best.''
</P>
<P>
   In the four years since their divorce, Benjamin, 12, and his
brother, Adam, 10, who survived the accident, were still able to
move freely between the houses while Vaughn and his ex-wife, Paula,
shared custody.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very unusual situation, and a wonderful, wonderful
picture to watch,'' neighbor Eleanor Johnson said. ''You couldn't
find a family more devoted and family oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson watched as Paula Vaughn sank to her knees in grief as
police broke the news after her morning run Sunday. She and her
parents flew to Switzerland to join Adam.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin was a precocious child, skilled at the violin and
piano, and was comfortable holding conversations with adults and
children alike.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was just a great kid -- sweet-natured,'' said neighbor Beth
Marsh-Doyle, whose son Matt was friends with Benjamin. ''Just a
wonderful child in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt, 10, said he'd talk to Benjamin about everything from food
to his favorite movies. They enjoyed water fights with hoses and
squirt guns.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a good role model,'' Matt said. ''He was never mean to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vaughn was remembered by neighbors for his devotion to his
boys. Every school day, Vaughn would wait at the bus stop before
heading to his Boston law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn earned his law degree from Boston University and later
became one of the top commercial real estate lawyers in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But next to his kids, Vaughn's job took a back seat, Toelke
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had a great position in a prestigious firm,'' Toelke said,
''but compared to his kids, it was nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2150 </TRAILER>
