<DOCNO> APW20000807.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another person added to list of those sickened by E. coli  </HEADLINE>
By CARRIE ANTLFINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) - Another person has been linked to an E. coli
outbreak at two local Sizzler restaurants that killed a 3-year-old
and sickened dozens of customers, including one from Long Island,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, 57 cases have been linked to a south side
Milwaukee Sizzler and two to a Wauwatosa Sizzler, health officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   They are investigating the possibility that some infections were
caused by person-to-person contact.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are concerned about secondary transmission,'' said Paul
Biedrzycki, manager of disease control and prevention for the
Milwaukee Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''It probably has occurred. To what degree I don't know, but not
to the degree of large numbers of people getting sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Biedrzycki said the number of cases could continue rising if
customers were exposed to the bacteria up until the restaurants
were closed.
</P>
<P>
   It can take up to eight days for symptoms to appear, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The south side location closed July 26. The Wauwatosa franchise
closed August 2.
</P>
<P>
   Most confirmed victims ate at the Sizzlers between July 12 and
21.
</P>
<P>
   Last week nine lawsuits were filed relating to the outbreak,
including a wrongful death suit on behalf of 3-year-old Brianna
Kriefall.
</P>
<P>
   She died July 28 from complications of hemolytic uremic syndrome
(HUS), a kidney disease caused by the E. coli infection, after
eating at the Milwaukee restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Gabrielle Cetta, a 4-year-old girl at Children's Hospital in New
York, remained in stable but improving condition Monday. Cetta, of
Long Island, became ill after eating at the Milwaukee Sizzler while
visiting relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Hospital of Wisconsin reported Monday that there were
two children still being treated there for E. coli infection, but
only one was related to Sizzler food.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the children was not released but neither were
in intensive care, a hospital spokeswoman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-07-00 2152 </TRAILER>
