<DOCNO> APW20000807.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Does Flourishes in Polls  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush is flourishing in the polls,
but a majority of Americans in two surveys released Monday don't
consider him to be ''a different kind of Republican'' as claimed by
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News poll said 35 percent consider the GOP presidential
nominee a different Republican, while 52 percent said he is ''a
typical Republican.'' An ABC News-Washington Post poll had similar
results on that question, with 35 percent saying he was different
and 56 percent saying he's the same as other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Despite skepticism about that claim, Bush led Gore by 16 points
in the CBS poll of registered voters, 50 percent to 34 percent,
while Ralph Nader had 5 percent and Pat Buchanan had 1 percent. And
he led by 14 points in the ABC-Post poll, 51 percent to 37 percent
with Nader at 5 percent and Buchanan at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has leads ranging from 11 points to 18 points in polls that
have been taken since the end of the GOP nominating convention last
week. His lead increased from 6 points before the convention to 15
points afterward in the CBS poll and from 9 points before the
convention to 14 points afterward in the ABC-Post survey.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have made gains in the last year on the public's
trust for them to be tolerant, with 35 percent saying that now
compared with 21 percent saying that in March of 1999. In the
ABC-Post poll, nearly half, 46 percent, trusted Democrats to be
tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   The public remains divided on whether the country needs to
change direction from Clinton's leadership, with 48 percent
preferring a change and 44 percent favoring the current direction.
Bush and running mate Dick Cheney raised that issue in convention
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   While a majority of the public doesn't view Bush as ''a
different kind of Republican, more than half believe he cares about
the problems of blacks and other minorities, according to the CBS
poll.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS poll of 868 registered voters and the ABC-Post poll of
975 registered voters were taken Friday through Sunday and have
error margins of 3 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2153 </TRAILER>
