<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, Aug. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore's VP Pick Is Lieberman
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rounding out the Democratic ticket with the first Jewish
vice presidential candidate for a major party in American history, Al Gore
selected Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman to be his running mate today. Gore
offered the spot on the ticket in a telephone call at midday, and Lieberman
accepted, having known for hours that the job was his. ''That was the call. It
was directly from Al Gore,'' Lieberman said, pulling up to his house in New
Haven, Conn., with a cell phone to his ear. ''We said a short prayer together,''
the senator said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Verizon Labor Talks Adjourn
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Negotiators wrapped up the day's formal talks between
Verizon Communications, the Northeast's leading local telephone company, and
striking union members around 8 p.m. EDT. They expected to begin talking again
tomorrow morning. The talks hit a snag earlier over several issues, including
the shifting of work to areas that are not as heavily unionized or where the pay
scale is lower. The strike by 87,200 company employees affects operations for 25
million customers from Maine to Virginia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Flourishes in Polls
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush is flourishing in the polls, but a majority
of Americans in two surveys released today don't consider him to be ''a
different kind of Republican'' as claimed by his campaign. A CBS News poll said
35 percent consider the GOP presidential nominee a different Republican, while
52 percent said he is ''a typical Republican.'' An ABC News-Washington Post poll
had similar results on that question, with 35 percent saying he was different
and 56 percent saying he's the same as other Republicans.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yugoslavia Protests Albanian Office
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Yugoslavia protested to the U.N. Security Council on
Monday against an Albanian liaison office in Kosovo, saying it would fuel
Albania's hopes of splitting the province from Yugoslavia. In a letter to the
council making the ''strongest protest,'' Yugoslav envoy Vladislav Jovanovic
called the opening of the Albanian office an unlawful act of ''diplomatic
piracy'' that will promote Albania's ''illegitimate and hostile claims'' to
Kosovo. He asked the council to annul a U.N. regulation allowing foreign
missions to open in Kosovo.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Venezuela Leader Visits Saudis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Saudi Arabia and Venezuela are intent on
ensuring a stable oil market with a goal of an average oil price of $25 a
barrel, officials said Tuesday after Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez opened a
tour of OPEC nations. Chavez met late Monday with Saudi King Fahd and Crown
Prince Abdullah in the Red Sea port city of Jiddah. No official statements
followed the meeting, which ended early Tuesday. A Venezuelan source, however,
said afterward that the two sides agreed the current OPEC production level is
sufficient so there is no need for additional supplies this summer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: Failing to Test Osteoporosis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Doctors are failing to test women who suffer wrist
fractures for osteoporosis, even though treatment often proves effective and the
same women face a greater risk of more serious bone fractures, new research
says. The study of 1,162 women over age 54 who suffered wrist fractures found
that only 33 patients underwent a bone density scan to detect the presence of
osteoporosis and only 266 were treated with medication for the disease. Those
women are nearly twice as likely to have hip fractures.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Netscape Flaw Infects Almost 1,000
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A security hole in Netscape's Web browser infected almost
1,000 computers today. Security experts were warning Internet users that once a
computer is infected, a hacker can see, run and delete files on the target
computer.''Netscape takes all security issues very seriously,'' said Netscape
spokesman Andrew Weinstein, ''We're working to quickly evaluate and address this
concern.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Tuesday on profit-taking following
sharp gains the previous day. The dollar was higher against the yen. The Nikkei
shed 70.92 points, or 0.44 percent, to 15,931.79 in early trading. In New York,
the Dow rose 99.26 points to 10,867.01 at Monday's close. The Nasdaq gained
75.63 points to close at 3,862.99.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Twins Beat Devil Rays 4-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Redman became the first American League
rookie to win 10 games this season, giving up four hits in 8 2-3 innings tonight
to lead the Minnesota Twins over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays 4-2. Redman (10-5)
struck out nine and walked two to win for the fifth time in his last six starts.
Minnesota has won 11 of its past 17 games. The Devil Rays lost for just the
fourth time in 12 games.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
</TEXT>
