<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Says Americans Bias  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE COPANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A top Palestinian negotiator on Monday accused
the United States of favoring Israel and said American pressure on
the Palestinians was hampering efforts to reach a final peace
agreement by Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Qureia, one of the top negotiators at a failed summit at
Camp David last month, warned that another summit would only be a
''trap'' if the United States and Israel do not recognize
Palestinian rights to east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In order for another round of talks to be possible, either
Israel must agree to divide the disputed city or the United States
must issue ''a letter of guarantees specifying its real positions
and not those positions biased toward the Israelis,'' Qureia said.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S.-mediated summit, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
had offered the Palestinians some control in east Jerusalem,
including in the walled Old City, but Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat demanded full sovereignty over the sector Israel captured in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   The sides are under heavy pressure to complete an agreement
quickly. Arafat says he will declare a state on Sept. 13. Israel
has said it will retaliate by annexing parts of the Gaza Strip and
West Bank. That could lead to violence.
</P>
<P>
   Qureia said he doubted the sides could reach an agreement before
the date, which the sides had set as a deadline for the completion
of the final peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see that the atmosphere and the mentality are such
that they could lead to a fair agreement,'' said Qureia, who is
speaker of the Palestinian parliament. ''The Israelis are still
thinking of blackmailing us while the Americans are still thinking
of putting pressure on us.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that the illusion on the Israeli and the American sides
that we can agree on what is less than our rights is finished,''
Qureia added. ''We will not walk into a trap.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and American attempts to force the Palestinians to agree
to less than full sovereignty in east Jerusalem -- particularly the
Al-Aqsa mosque, the third holiest site to Muslims -- runs counter to
the positions of Arab nations as well, Qureia said.
</P>
<P>
   The Old City also houses sites holy to Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was visiting the Persian Gulf region Monday, hoping to
garner support for his plans to declare statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Senior U.S. Mideast envoy, Dennis B. Ross, is expected to resume
his talks with Israel and the Palestinians in the region Aug. 20.
to determine if the sides are ready for another round of formal
talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2215 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
