<HEADLINE> Orioles 4, Tigers 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ivanon Coffie hit a tiebreaking sacrifice fly in
the ninth inning and Brady Anderson homered to lead the Baltimore
Orioles over the Detroit Tigers 4-3 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 3-all, Chris Richard led off the ninth with a
double off Doug Brocail (5-4) and advanced on Brook Fordyce's
groundout. Coffie then lifted fly to center that was just deep
enough to score Richard.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Groom (4-3) struck out the only batter he faced, Bobby
Higginson in the eighth, and Ryan Kohlmeier pitched a perfect ninth
for his first major league save, sealing Baltimore's sixth win in
nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Palmer homered for the Tigers, 1-4 on a seven-game
homestand. They stranded 11 runners -- eight in scoring position --
and left the bases full in both the fifth and sixth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Neither rookie starter figured in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles left-hander John Parrish, making his third major league
start, allowed two runs, eight hits and five walks in 5 1-3
innings, leaving with a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit right-hander Adam Bernero, making his second major
league start and appearance, gave up three runs and six hits in 6
2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Delino DeShields' RBI single but Baltimore ahead in the third,
with Melvin Mora thrown out at the plate by center fielder Juan
Encarnacion on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Ausmus' run-scoring grounder tied it in the bottom half,
but the Orioles went back ahead in the fourth when Jeff Conine
tripled and scored on Brook Fordyce's sacrifice fly, dropped by
Encarnacion for a two-base error.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson made it 3-1 with a solo homer in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit loaded the bases with two outs in the home half, but
Parrish struck out Juan Gonzalez on a 2-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer led off the sixth with his 21st home run, and the Tigers
loaded the bases again with one out to knock out Parrish. But Mike
Trombley relieved and retired Damion Easley and Ausmus on grounders
to third.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Billy McMillon tied it with an RBI double in the
seventh off Trombley.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Tigers ran themselves out of the first inning after
Easley hit a leadoff single and Ausmus walked. Parrish caught
Easley leaning off second and ran him down for the first out, then
threw to Mora at shortstop to throw out Ausmus trying to steal.
Bobby Higginson then walked, but Gonzalez flied out, ending the
inning. ... Albert Belle was 0-for-4 and is hitting just .196
(11-for-56) in his last 14 games. ... Chris Richard was 1-for-5 and
has hit safely in all seven games since the Orioles obtained him
July 29 from St. Louis for Mike Timlin. ... Gonzalez was 0-for-5
with two strikeouts and stranded six runners. He's 1-for-17 during
the homestand.
</P>
</TEXT>
