<HEADLINE> Mobil to reimburse DEC for cleanup of Oil City sites  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - Mobil Oil Corporation has become the third
oil company to agree to partially reimburse the state for cleanup
of two city blocks dubbed ''Oil City'' because of contamination
left by more than a century of fuel storage tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfax, Va.-based company will pay $100,000. In addition,
the company has agreed to perform remediation measures on the soil.
</P>
<P>
   ''This agreement will ensure that these contaminated sites are
properly cleaned up and help pave the way for the redevelopment of
Oil City and Syracuse's Inner Harbor,'' state Department of
Environmental Conservation Commissioner John Cahill said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Included in that redevelopment is the planned $200 million
expansion of Pyramid's Carousel Center mall, reportedly on delay
because of the pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Pyramid officials told the DEC they were ''frustrated'' with the
slow pace of the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   The Citgo and Sunoco oil companies previously signed similar
consent orders.
</P>
</TEXT>
