<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Summit Ends  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) -- Southern African leaders pressed the
warring parties in Congo on Monday to join a dialogue as part of
the peace process aiming to end the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   But the Heads of state from the 14-nation Southern African
Development Community, who ended their annual summit Monday,
postponed addressing Congo President Laurent Kabila's rejection of
the mediator for the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   In a final statement, the leaders insisted the Congolese peace
process was still on track, despite repeated violations of
cease-fires and other setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Congo has been wracked by civil war with Uganda and Rwanda
backing Congolese rebels and Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe
supporting Kabila. Kabila did not show up for the summit.
</P>
<P>
   The summit urged the Congolese to honor their agreements by
supporting an internal political dialogue under former Botswana
President Sir Ketumile Masire, who Kabila has adamantly rejected as
a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's refusal to accept Masire will be discussed at a special
meeting on Congo to be held in Lusaka, Zambia, on August 14,
Namibian President Sam Nujoma said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will never give up,'' said Nujoma, the incoming SADC
chairman for the next year.
</P>
<P>
   The SADC leaders also supported beleaguered Zimbabwe and
condemned the U.S. Congress' passage of a bill that would impose a
series of political conditions on the country in return for
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing SADC chairman Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano and
Nujoma told reporters that Zimbabwe's June parliamentary elections
had been free and fair, despite international observers
condemnation of pre-election violence that killed more than 30
people and left thousands of others, mainly opposition supporters,
battered.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as I am concerned, the elections were free and fair,''
said Nujoma, a staunch ally of embattled President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   SADC's acting secretary-general, Prega Ramsamy, said the meeting
led to progress in terms of regional agricultural development,
infrastructure and energy issues.
</P>
<P>
   The final statement also called for urgent action on combatting
the HIV/AIDS pandemic sweeping the continent and praised the
general political stability and respect for human rights the region
has enjoyed over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   But Chissano cautioned that the region would have to register
annual economic growth in excess of 6 percent if the leaders were
to make a dent in widespread poverty.
</P>
<P>
   SADC hoped that by implementing a Free Trade Area beginning next
month, the increasingly free flow of goods and people could help
achieve this target, Chissano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2228 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000807.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safir to announce he's leaving NYPD  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Police Commissioner Howard Safir, who has
presided over a department beset by racial incidents at the same
time that crime has dropped dramatically, will be leaving the NYPD
next month, police sources with direct knowledge of Safir's plans
confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Three sources, all speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Safir is expected to make the announcement at a yet-to-be scheduled
news conference Tuesday, but they were not certain whether he is
going to another job, or if his decision had anything to do with
the diagnosis in May that he has prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Safir's spokeswoman, Marilyn Mode, did not immediately respond
to requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir told WPIX-TV Channel 11 that there would be an
announcement on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is that there will be some change,'' he said. ''But I
don't want to talk about it until the mayor actually announces it.
He and I will do it together as we have done most things
together.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his time as police commissioner ''the best job that
I'll ever have in my entire life,'' while saying the most difficult
aspect has been ''when we bury police officers, and any time we
lose a police officer that's still the hardest part of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir, 58, was appointed police commissioner in 1996 by his good
friend, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whom he has known for more than 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Safir was often deemed by his critics as being merely Giuliani's
puppet at Police Headquarters, rubber-stamping the mayor's
policies. Safir was never as popular as his predecessor, the
affable William Bratton, who won over the men and women in blue, as
well as the public.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir followed up on many of Bratton's initiatives,
including COMPSTAT - a computer tracking of crime statistics, and
the crackdown on ''quality of life'' offenders, such as jaywalkers
and squeegee men, and crime fell during his watch.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of controversial incidents have dogged Safir. In
1997, Haitian immigrant Abner Louima was brutalized in the bathroom
of the 70th Precinct in Brooklyn by Officer Justin Volpe. Volpe
pleaded guilty in 1999. Five other officers have either been
convicted at trial or pleaded guilty in one of the worst police
brutality scandals in city history.
</P>
<P>
   After the incident, Safir transferred the entire precinct,
bringing in a number of Hispanic and black officers in hopes of
appeasing the mostly minority community that precinct serves. But
in June, a federal jury ordered the police department to pay 24
officers $50,000 each for being involuntarily transferred.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1999, four white police officers fatally gunned down
West African immigrant Amadou Diallo in his Bronx apartment
vestibule because they thought the wallet he was holding was a gun.
All of the officers were acquitted in February of murder and other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the shooting, Safir took an all-expenses-paid trip
to the Academy Awards, courtesy of a Revlon executive friend,
leaving town amid the protests over Diallo's death.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar trip prompted the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association -
the union representing more than 26,000 cops - to issue its
first-ever ''no-confidence'' vote against a commissioner. Safir
refused to quit and reiterated a statement he has made many times
during his tenure: ''Crime has gone down more under my stewardship
than any time in the history of this city. ... It is a safer
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir - and Giuliani - were mired in controversy again when in
March, an undercover detective fatally shot Patrick Dorismond, an
unarmed security guard, on a Manhattan street known as a drug
location. However, Dorismond did not have any drugs on him. Both
Safir and the mayor were heavily criticized for releasing
Dorismond's sealed juvenile record. A state grand jury declined to
indict the detective.
</P>
<P>
   Safir suffered a personal blow in May, when he was diagnosed
with prostate cancer. When he made his diagnosis public, just weeks
after Giuliani announced that he was suffering from prostate
cancer, Safir said his condition was treatable, but has not
disclosed his treatment plan.
</P>
<P>
   Safir was appointed the city's 39th police commissioner after a
stint as fire commissioner. He had earlier spent 26 years in
federal law enforcement, serving with the Drug Enforcement
Administration and later as operations chief of the U.S. Marshals
Service in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He then formed his own security consulting firm, Safir
Associates, based in Fairfax, Va. In 1994, the Bronx native
returned to the city to serve in Giuliani's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Safir graduated from Hofstra University in 1963 with a bachelor
of arts degree in history and political science, and went on to
Brooklyn Law School. He and his wife have been married for 34
years. They have two adult children, Adam and Jennifer, both of
whom are married.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
