<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safir To Announce He's Leaving  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- New York City's police commissioner will step
down next month after a four-year stint that included a dramatic
drop in crime but several racial incidents that damaged the
department's image.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Safir is expected to make the announcement at a news
conference Tuesday, according to three sources with direct
knowledge of his plans.
</P>
<P>
   The sources who spoke on condition of anonymity were not certain
whether Safir is going to another job, or if his decision had
anything to do with the diagnosis in May that he has prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Safir told WPIX-TV Channel 11 that there would be an
announcement on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is that there will be some change,'' he said. ''But I
don't want to talk about it until the mayor actually announces it.
He and I will do it together as we have done most things
together.''
</P>
<P>
   He called his time as police commissioner ''the best job that
I'll ever have in my entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir, 58, was appointed police commissioner in 1996 by his good
friend, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, whom he has known for more than 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   Safir was often deemed by his critics as being merely Giuliani's
puppet at police headquarters, rubber-stamping the mayor's
policies. Safir was never as popular as his predecessor, the
affable William Bratton, who won over police officers as well as
the public.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir followed up on many of Bratton's initiatives, and
crime fell during his watch.
</P>
<P>
   A number of controversial incidents have dogged Safir, including
the 1997 beating of a Haitian immigrant by an officer at a Brooklyn
precinct; the slaying of an African immigrant in 1999 by officers
who thought the wallet he was holding was a gun; and the March
shooting of an unarmed security guard by an undercover detective.
</P>
<P>
   Safir also sparked controversy when he took an all-expenses-paid
trip to the Academy Awards, courtesy of a Revlon executive friend,
amid protests over the death of the African immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   When Safir made his cancer diagnosis public in May, just weeks
after Giuliani announced that he was suffering from prostate
cancer, Safir said his condition was treatable, but has not
disclosed his treatment plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
