<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, Aug. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Picks Lieberman for Vice President
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore selected Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman to be
his running mate today, rounding out the Democratic ticket with the first Jewish
vice presidential candidate for a major party in American history. Gore offered
the spot on the ticket in a telephone call at midday, and Lieberman accepted,
having known for hours that the job was his. ''That was the call. It was
directly from Al Gore,'' Lieberman said, pulling up to his house in New Haven,
Conn., with a cell phone to his ear. ''We said a short prayer together,'' the
senator said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Malaysia Leader Guilty of Sodomy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- A former Malaysian deputy prime minister was
convicted of sodomy Tuesday, a widely expected verdict that ended Anwar
Ibrahim's two-year battle against what he has called a political conspiracy
against him. High Court Judge Ariffin Jaka announced his ruling in a packed
courtroom. Lawyers for both sides went immediately into sentencing hearings.
Tuesday's judgment ends a yearlong trial, the second for Anwar since he was
fired by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad in 1998.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Safir To Announce He's Leaving
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- New York City's police commissioner will step down next
month after a four-year stint that included a dramatic drop in crime but several
racial incidents that damaged the department's image. Howard Safir is expected
to make the announcement at a news conference Tuesday, according to three
sources with direct knowledge of his plans. The sources who spoke on condition
of anonymity were not certain whether Safir is going to another job, or if his
decision had anything to do with the diagnosis in May that he has prostate
cancer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Verizon Labor Talks Adjourn
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Negotiators finished up the day's formal talks between
Verizon Communications, the Northeast's leading local telephone company, and
striking union members around 8 p.m. EDT. They expected to resume talking again
tomorrow morning. The talks hit a snag earlier over several issues, including
the shifting of work to areas that are not as heavily unionized or where the pay
scale is lower. The strike by 87,200 company employees affects operations for 25
million customers from Maine to Virginia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Palestinian Says Americans Bias
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A top Palestinian negotiator on Monday accused the United
States of favoring Israel and said American pressure on the Palestinians was
hampering efforts to reach a final peace agreement by Sept. 13. Ahmed Qureia,
one of the top negotiators at a failed summit at Camp David last month, warned
that another summit would only be a ''trap'' if the United States and Israel do
not recognize Palestinian rights to east Jerusalem.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Venezuela Leader Visits Saudis
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Saudi Arabia and Venezuela are intent on
ensuring a stable oil market with a goal of an average oil price of $25 a
barrel, officials said Tuesday after Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez opened a
tour of OPEC nations. Chavez met late Monday with Saudi King Fahd and Crown
Prince Abdullah in the Red Sea port city of Jiddah. No official statements
followed the meeting, which ended early Tuesday. A Venezuelan source, however,
said afterward that the two sides agreed the current OPEC production level is
sufficient so there is no need for additional supplies this summer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Standard Infant Screening Sought
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- All newborns in Maine, but not neighboring New Hampshire, are
routinely tested for a sometimes fatal metabolic disease called MCAD. In
Colorado, they're tested for sickle cell disease, but not across the state line
in Utah. Concerned by such inconsistencies, the American Academy of Pediatrics
wants the federal government to adopt uniform testing standards for the 4
million infants born nationwide each year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Tuesday on profit-taking following
sharp gains the previous day. The dollar was higher against the yen. The Nikkei
shed 70.92 points, or 0.44 percent, to 15,931.79 in early trading. In New York,
the Dow rose 99.26 points to 10,867.01 at Monday's close. The Nasdaq gained
75.63 points to close at 3,862.99.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Orioles Beat Tigers 4-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ivanon Coffie hit a tiebreaking sacrifice fly in the ninth
inning and Brady Anderson homered to lead the Baltimore Orioles over the Detroit
Tigers 4-3 tonight. With the score 3-all, Chris Richard led off the ninth with a
double off Doug Brocail and advanced on Brook Fordyce's groundout. Coffie then
lifted fly to center that was just deep enough to score Richard.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
