<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Friends Cite Character  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Sen. Joseph Lieberman needs to take the
pulse of Connecticut voters, he heads to a diner and asks his
constituents to ''have a cup of joe'' with Joe. He says it's the
best way to get unfiltered views.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, aides estimate he has visited more than 100 Connecticut
diners. And while he seeks diverse opinions, Lieberman sticks to a
standard order: a tuna fish sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation for steady habits, a resolute manner and
faithfulness to his beliefs has won him fans among Republicans as
well as Democrats. Now he's Al Gore's vice presidential running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm delighted. He's my favorite Democrat,'' said former
Education Secretary William Bennett, a Republican adviser to the
presidential campaign of George W. Bush. ''They've got a serious
person. ... He's arguably the most impressive Democrat in the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until two years ago, not many people knew the 58-year-old
Orthodox Jewish senator outside of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   That changed with a Sept. 3, 1998, speech on the Senate floor in
which he chastised President Clinton -- his friend of almost 30
years -- for Clinton's affair with White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. He described Clinton's behavior as ''disgraceful'' and
''embarrassing'' to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Though he eventually voted to acquit the president of
impeachment charges, the speech boosted Lieberman's reputation as a
moral crusader. Fellow Democrats dubbed him the ''conscience of the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman made his comments despite his long friendship with
Clinton, dating back to their days at Yale Law School. In 1970, as
a student, Clinton campaigned for Lieberman when he was running for
a state senate district that included Yale. In 1992, Lieberman
returned the favor, speaking up as the first senator from the
Northeast to endorse Clinton's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to his wife, Hadassah, is the second for each of
them. He and his first wife, Elizabeth, divorced in 1981 after 16
years and have two grown children together, Matthew, 32, and
Rebecca, 31.
</P>
<P>
   He and Hadassah were married in 1983, she bringing her son from
her previous marriage, Ethan, to the family. Ethan is 24. The
Liebermans live in New Haven with the daughter they had together,
Hana, 12. Lieberman also has two granddaughters, Tennessee and
Willie.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was born in Stamford to Marcia and Henry Lieberman.
The father was a liquor store salesman. The son attended public
schools before heading to Yale as an undergraduate in 1964. He
graduated from Yale Law School in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   He won the state Senate seat in 1970, and served the New Haven
area district for 10 years. He was elected state attorney general
in 1983 and stayed in that office until his 1988 run for U.S.
Senate against Republican incumbent Lowell P. Weicker. Lieberman
won by just 10,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   His re-election in 1994 was a landslide. He beat Republican
Gerald Labriola by some 350,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's politics, though Democratic, have always leaned
somewhat to the right, some say, pointing to his support for
increased defense spending and school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Lieberman and Bennett began handing out ''Silver
Sewer Awards'' to single out producers of sexually explicit and
violent films, music, television programs and video games.
</P>
<P>
   Critics call him a liberal who votes for abortion rights, gun
control and tax hikes. Philip Giordano, Lieberman's challenger for
re-election to the Senate this year, says, ''He looks like the
pillar of morality, but then he goes with his party line.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. John G. Rowland, though endorsing Giordano,
called Lieberman ''a great friend of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters talk most often of his character.
</P>
<P>
   ''His integrity and commitment to good values are the most
impressive things about him,'' said Rabbi Barry Fruendel of Kesher
Israel, the synagogue Lieberman attends in Washington. ''He's not
afraid to put life's most important things in front of politics.''	   His
religion itself is notable. He is the first Jewish vice
presidential candidate on a major-party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Because he and his wife observe the Jewish Sabbath from sundown
Friday to sundown Saturday, Lieberman adjusts his work schedule.
</P>
<P>
   His religion immediately raised questions about how he would
deal with Middle East matters. But Faisal Husseini, a top official
with the Palestinian Liberation Organization in Jerusalem, said,
''I hope that when he is in such a position that he will look at
the issue through a wider lens and make balanced decisions. I
believe he can do so because he is informed about the Middle
East.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
