<DOCNO> APW20000807.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bhutan-India Floods Kill Over 200  </HEADLINE>
By WASBIR HUSSAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAUHATI, India (AP) -- Monsoon rains that left 2.5 million
Indians homeless in the northeast have hit the neighboring kingdom
of Bhutan, killing nearly 200 people, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At least 180 bodies had been recovered as of Sunday in Pashaka,
a village in Bhutan close to the Indian border that was pounded by
mudslides, United News of India reported.
</P>
<P>
   The village was destroyed, the agency quoted Indian officials in
the border Jalpaiguri district as saying. More villagers were
feared dead.
</P>
<P>
   The swollen Dhuti Khola River has submerged much of the tiny
kingdom's main economic center, the town of Phuntsholing, under
water in the past week, the Bhutanese government-owned Kuensel
weekly newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Bhutanese soldiers and policemen have been asked to carry
food, medicine and tents for hundreds of people left homeless. The
telephone links have also been snapped between major towns in
Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
   To help rescue efforts, the Indian army has sent troops to the
flood-hit areas across the border, UNI said.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Bangladesh, torrential rains and overflowing rivers
flooded hundreds of villages, leaving at least 12 people dead and
thousands of others stranded or homeless, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Indian side, the death toll has risen to 80 in 16
flood-hit districts of Assam state, government officials said.
Those hit by the floods were facing a severe shortage of food and
medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are virtually starving with nothing to eat. Whatever we
managed to carry, as we fled our homes on Thursday when flood
waters entered our homes, has now finished,'' said Dhruva Das, a
resident of village Borbhag in Nalbari district, 75 miles west of
Gauhati, the capital of Assam state, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of infants and elderly people have developed symptoms
of dysentery and other waterborne diseases in relief camps.
</P>
<P>
   The flood waters have been receding since Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than 2,500 villagers have been rescued so far by the Air
Force helicopters,'' said S. Madhok, an army commander in Rangiya,
30 miles west of Gauhati.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-07-00 2312 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000807.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-07 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Doctors Bound for Miami  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Two Cuban doctors jailed in Zimbabwe for more than
a month after defecting from a medical mission arrived in Miami
Monday night after nearly a month's temporary refuge in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Leonel Cordova Rodriguez, 31, and Noris Pena Martinez, 25, left
Stockholm on a morning flight, with stopovers in Zurich,
Switzerland, and New York. About 30 people greeted them when they
arrived in Miami, two held Cuban flags and one held a sign that
said ''Bienvenidos Doctores'' (Welcome Doctors).
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered loudly and sang the Cuban national anthem when
the doctors arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a product of the new generations coming out of Cuba and as
a doctor or professional, I felt like a slave in the Cuban state,''
Pena Martinez said. ''I have defected, seeking freedom, just as the
majority of the young professionals in Cuba would like to enjoy in
a free and democratic Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova Rodriguez said that his family in Cuba was kicked out of
their home because of his defection.
</P>
<P>
   ''My family is suffering, they're suffering a lot ... Now they
are out living with the help of friends at the mercy of the
state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pena Martinez plans to stay with her second cousin, Mina
Fernandez, who helped lead efforts in the local Cuban exile
community on behalf of the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're happy that she got out of Zimbabwe,'' Fernandez said.
''It was not easy to get them out of there. Thank God for the help
of the politicians and the U.S. government for getting them the
temporary visas ... Fidel Castro lost this battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban American National Foundation, a powerful Miami-based
anti-Castro Cuban exile group, has pledged to help the pair find
jobs here.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova Rodriguez intended to stay with Emilio de-Quesada, 45,
who taught the doctor when he was a student at the University of
Havana medical school. De-Quesdada said he would help guide his
former student through adjustment to life in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ''He doesn't have the slightest idea what life is like here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pena Martinez, a dentist, and Cordova Rodriguez, a physician,
were hoping to find work as assistants in their fields, and both
planned to go through the lengthy process of getting their Cuban
degrees revalidated in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The pair arrived in Stockholm on July 8 after the U.N. High
Commission for Refugees negotiated their release from jail and
Swedish immigration authorities issued them two-month visas while
they applied for refugee status in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Their refugee status, which was granted just over a week ago,
will allow them to apply for permanent residency after one year in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova Rodriguez and Pena Martinez were in Zimbabwe on a
medical mission when they sought refuge at the Canadian and U.S.
embassies in Harare, which referred them to the U.N. commission.
But the Cubans disappeared June 2, the day of their hearing before
a Zimbabwean asylum committee.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors accused Zimbabwean security officers of kidnapping
them and helping Cuban diplomats try to force them on a flight to
Havana. Air France refused to let them board during a stopover in
South Africa after the doctors slipped a note to a crew member
saying they were kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors were returned to Zimbabwe and jailed, while the U.N.
refugee agency demanded their release under international law.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba said the doctors betrayed the medical mission to aid
Zimbabwe's health service but denied any involvement in the alleged
kidnapping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
